{"title_page": "Telegram (software)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Telegram (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Free cross-platform messenging service}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Telegram<!--Technical ID; must not be changed. Use \"title\" to change what is displayed instead.-->\n| title = Telegram Messenger\n| logo = Telegram 2019 Logo.svg\n| screenshot = Telegram Chats List on iOS.png\n| screenshot size = 220px\n| caption = Telegram running on an [[iPhone]]\n| developer = Telegram FZ LLC<br>Telegram Messenger Inc.\n| released = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2013|8|14|}}\n| ver layout = stacked\n| programming language = [[C++]]\n| platform = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Windows Phone]], [[Windows NT]], [[macOS]], [[GNU/Linux]], [[Web app|Web platform]]\n| language count = 14\n| language footnote = <ref>{{cite web|title=Live Locations, Media Player and Languages|url=https://telegram.org/blog/live-locations|website=telegram.org|publisher=Telegram Messenger LLP|accessdate= 12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Translating Telegram|url=https://translations.telegram.org/|website=translations.telegram.org|publisher=Telegram Messenger LLP|accessdate= 12 April 2018}}</ref>\n| language = [[English language|English]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[German language|German]], [[Dutch language|Dutch]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Arabic]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[French language|French]], [[Languages of Indonesia|Indonesian]], [[Malay language|Malay]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n| genre = [[Instant messaging]]\n| license = [[GNU General Public License|GNU GPLv2 or GPLv3]] (clients),<ref name=\"teleapps\" /> proprietary (server)\n| alexa = {{DecreasePositive}} 188 ({{asof|2020|04|13|alt=April 2020}})<ref>{{cite web |title=telegram.org Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic - Alexa |url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/telegram.org |website=alexa.com |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|https://telegram.org}}\n}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name             = Telegram Messenger LLP\n| logo             = [[File:Telegram 2019 Logo.svg|100px]]\n| collapsible      = \n| screenshot       = \n| caption          = \n| dissolved        =\n| location         = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]<br>(legal domicile)<br>[[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]]<br>(operational center)\n| locations        = \n| founder          = {{Unbulleted list|[[Nikolai Durov]]|[[Pavel Durov]]}}\n| chairman         = \n| chairperson      = \n| president        = \n| CEO              = Pavel Durov\n| MD               =\n| GM               = \n| industry         = [[Software]]\n| products         = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            =\n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| url              = {{URL|https://telegram.org/}}\n| advertising      = \n| language         =\n| footnotes        = \n| logo_size        = \n| company_type     = \n| traded_as        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|2013|3}}\n| incorporated     =\n| area_served      = Global\n| key_people       = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| num_employees    = 351 (2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://craft.co/telegram-messenger|title=Telegram Company profile|date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n| subsid           = \n| programming_language = \n| website_type     =\n| num_users        =\n| launch_date      = \n| current_status   = \n| collapsetext     = \n}}\n'''Telegram''' is a [[Cloud computing|cloud]]-based [[instant messaging]] and [[voice over IP]] service. Telegram [[client (computing)|client]] apps are available for [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Windows Phone]], [[Windows NT]], [[macOS]] and [[GNU/Linux]].<ref name=\"teleapps\">{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/apps|title=List of Telegram applications|date=6 February 2014}}</ref> Users can send messages and exchange photos, videos, [[Sticker (messaging)|sticker]]s, audio and files of any type.\n\nTelegram's client-side code is [[open-source software]] but the source code for recent versions is not always immediately published,<ref name=\"GitHub\">{{cite web|url=https://github.com/DrKLO/Telegram/commits/master|title=Latest commits from official repository (Android version)|date=10 April 2016|website=Github|access-date=}}</ref> whereas its server-side code is closed-source and proprietary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-why-not-open-source-everything|title=Telegram F.A.Q.|website=Telegram|access-date=2017-10-01}}</ref> The service also provides [[Application programming interface|APIs]] to independent developers. In March 2018, Telegram stated that it had 200 million [[monthly active users]].<ref name=\"TelegramUsersMarch2018\">{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/200-million|title=200,000,000 Monthly Active Users|date=22 March 2018|website=Telegram}}</ref>\n\nDefault messages and media in Telegram are encrypted when stored on its servers, but can be accessed by the Telegram service provider, who holds the [[encryption key]]s. In addition Telegram provides optional [[End-to-end encryption|end-to-end encrypted]] \"secret\" chats between two online users, yet not for groups or channels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-why-not-just-make-all-chats-secret|title=Telegram F.A.Q.|website=Telegram|access-date=2017-10-01}}</ref>\n\nThe client-server communication is also encrypted.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://telegra.ph/Why-you-should-stop-reading-Gizmodo-right-now-Long|title=Why you should stop reading Gizmodo right now|date=2017-06-21|work=Telegraph|access-date=2017-10-01}}</ref> The service provides end-to-end encryption for voice calls.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://core.telegram.org/techfaq#q-how-are-voice-calls-authenticated|title=FAQ for the Technically Inclined|website=core.telegram.org|access-date=2017-10-01}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Development ===\nTelegram was launched in 2013 by the brothers [[Nikolai Durov|Nikolai]] and [[Pavel Durov]]. Previously, the pair founded the [[Russia]]n social network [[VK (social network)|VK]], which they left when it was taken over by the [[Mail.ru Group]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"TechCrunch\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/10/27/meet-telegram-a-secure-messaging-app-from-the-founders-of-vk-russias-largest-social-network/|title=Meet Telegram, A Secure Messaging App From The Founders Of VK, Russia\u2019s Largest Social Network|last=Shu|first=Catherine|date=27 October 2013|website=TechCrunch|access-date=18 March 2016}}</ref> Nikolai Durov created the [[MTProto]] protocol that is the basis for the messenger, while Pavel provided financial support and infrastructure through his [[Axel Neff#Digital Fortress LLC|Digital Fortress]] fund with partner [[Axel Neff]] joining as a second co-founder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/08/30/idUS74722569420130830|title=Russia's Zuckerberg launches Telegram, a new instant messenger service|date=30 August 2013|website=Reuters|access-date=18 March 2016}}</ref> Telegram Messenger LLP states that its end goal is not to bring profit,<ref>[https://telegram.org/faq#q-how-are-you-going-to-make-money-out-of-this Telegram F.A.Q], \"...making profits will never be an end-goal for Telegram.\"</ref><ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2014/2/25/5445864/telegram-messenger-hottest-app-in-the-world Why Telegram has become the hottest messaging app in the world], The Verge. Retrieved 25 February 2014. \"Telegram operates as a non-profit organization, and doesn\u2019t plan to charge for its services.\"</ref> but it is not currently structured as a non-profit organization.<ref name=\"WaPo1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-intersect/wp/2015/11/23/the-secret-american-origins-of-telegram-the-encrypted-messaging-app-favored-by-the-islamic-state/|title=The secret American origins of Telegram, the encrypted messaging app favored by the Islamic State|last1=Dewey|first1=Caitlin|date=November 23, 2015|accessdate=31 March 2018|publisher=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nTelegram is registered as both an English [[Limited liability partnership|LLP]]<ref>{{cite web|title = Telegram - Android Apps on Google Play|url = https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=org.telegram.messenger|website = play.google.com|accessdate = 19 November 2015}}</ref> and an American [[Limited liability company|LLC]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Telegram Messenger on the App Store|url = https://itunes.apple.com/app/telegram-messenger/id686449807|website = App Store|accessdate = 19 November 2015}}</ref> It does not disclose where it rents offices or which legal entities it uses to rent them, citing the need to \"shelter the team from unnecessary influence\" and protect users from governmental data requests.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Lunch with the FT: Pavel Durov|url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/21c5c7f2-20b1-11e5-ab0f-6bb9974f25d0.html|newspaper = [[Financial Times]]|access-date = 19 November 2015|first = John|last = Thornhill|date = 3 July 2015}}</ref> Pavel Durov has said that the service was headquartered in [[Berlin]], [[Germany]], between 2014<ref name=\"TheVergeKorea\">{{cite web|url = https://www.theverge.com/2014/10/6/6926205/surveillance-drives-south-koreans-to-encrypted-messaging-apps|title = Surveillance drives South Koreans to encrypted messaging apps|date = 6 October 2014|website = [[The Verge]]|accessdate = 19 November 2015|first = Russell|last = Brandom}}</ref> and early 2015, but moved to different jurisdictions after failing to obtain residence permits for everyone on the team.<ref name=\"Turton-2017-09-29\">{{cite web|last1=Turton|first1=William|title=What isn\u2019t Telegram saying about its connections to the Kremlin?|url=https://theoutline.com/post/2348/what-isn-t-telegram-saying-about-its-connections-to-the-kremlin|website=The Outline|accessdate=11 October 2017|date=29 September 2017}}</ref> Durov left Russia and is said to be moving from country to country with a small group of computer programmers consisting of 15 core members.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|title = Once Celebrated in Russia, the Programmer Pavel Durov Chooses Exile|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/03/technology/once-celebrated-in-russia-programmer-pavel-durov-chooses-exile.html|newspaper = [[The New York Times]]|date = 2 December 2014|access-date = 19 November 2015|first = Danny|last = Hakim}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-telecoms-mobileworld-telegram-idUSKCN0VW2CM|title=Telegram app free-speech advocate no stranger to Apple-FBI woes|date=23 February 2016|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref> According to press reports, Telegram had employees in [[St. Petersburg]].<ref name=\"Turton-2017-09-29\"/> The Telegram team is currently based in Dubai.<ref name=\"Bloomberg-2017-12-12\">{{cite news|title = This $5 Billion Encrypted App Isn't for Sale at Any Price | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-12/cryptic-russian-crusader-says-his-5-billion-app-can-t-be-bought|newspaper = [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] | date = 12 December 2017 |access-date = 22 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Usage numbers ===\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=400\n|height=160\n|type=line\n|xType=date\n|xAxisFormat=%b %Y\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|yGrid= \n|x=2013-08-14, 2013-10-27, 2014-01-26, 2014-03-24, 2014-12-08, 2015-09-21, 2016-02-23, 2017-12-12, 2018-03-22, 2020-04-18\n|y1=0, 0.2, 2, 35, 50, 60, 100, 180, 200, 400\n|xAxisTitle=Telegram \u0443\u0430\u049b\u044b\u0442\u0448\u0430 \u0448\u043a\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044b (\u0442\u0430\u043c\u044b\u0437 2013 \u2013 \u0441\u04d9\u0443\u0456\u0440 2020)\n|yAxisTitle=\u0410\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u044b\u043d\u0493\u044b \u0431\u0435\u043b\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0456 \u043f\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0443\u0448\u044b\u043b\u0430\u0440 (mil.)\n}}\nIn October 2013, Telegram had 100,000 daily active users.<ref name=\"TechCrunch\" /> On 24 March 2014, Telegram announced that it had reached 35 million monthly users and 15 million daily active users.<ref>{{Citation|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/03/24/telegram-hits-35m-monthly-users-15m-daily-with-8b-messages-received-over-30-days/|publisher=TechCrunch|title=Telegram Hits 35M Monthly Users, 15M Daily With 8B Messages Received Over 30 Days|date=24 Marth 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, South Korean governmental surveillance plans drove many of its citizens to switch to Telegram.<ref name=\"TheVergeKorea\" /> In December 2014, Telegram announced that it had 50 million active users, generating 1 billion daily messages, and that it had 1 million new users signing up on its service every week<ref>{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/billion|publisher=Telegram|title=Telegram Reaches 1 Billion Daily Messages|date=8 December 2014}}</ref>, traffic doubled in five months with 2 billion daily messages.<ref>{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/2-billion|publisher=Telegram|title=Telegram Hits 2 Billion Messages Sent Daily|date=13 May 2015}}</ref> In September 2015, an announcement stated that the app had 60 million active users and delivered 12 billion daily messages.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://techcrunch.com/2015/09/21/telegram-now-seeing-12bn-daily-messages-up-from-1m-in-february/|title = Telegram Now Seeing 12BN Daily Messages, up From 1BN in February|date = 21 September 2015|accessdate = 19 November 2015|website = [[Techcrunch]]|last = Lomas|first = Natasha}}</ref> In February 2016, Telegram announced that it had 100 million monthly active users, with 350,000 new users signing up every day, delivering 15 billion messages daily.<ref>{{cite web|title = Encrypted Messaging App Telegram Hits 100M Monthly Active Users, 350k New Users Each Day|url = https://techcrunch.com/2016/02/23/encrypted-messaging-app-telegram-hits-100m-monthly-active-users-350k-new-users-each-day/|website = TechCrunch|access-date = 23 February 2016|first = Matt|last = Burns|date = 23 February 2016}}</ref> In December 2017, Telegram reached 180 million monthly active users.<ref name=\"Bloomberg-2017-12-12\" /> In March 2018, Telegram reached 200 million monthly active users.<ref name=\"TelegramUsersMarch2018\"/> On March 14, 2019, Pavel Durov claimed that \u201c3 million new users signed up for Telegram within the last 24 hours.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lomas |first1=Natasha |title=Telegram gets 3M new signups during Facebook apps\u2019 outage |url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/03/14/telegram-gets-3m-new-signups-during-facebook-apps-outage/ |website=TechCrunch |accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref> Durov didn't specify what prompted this flood of new sign-ups, but the period matched a prolonged technical outage experienced by Facebook and its family of apps, including Instagram.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shieber |first1=Jonathan |title=Update: Facebook, Instagram and Messenger were down for many users |url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/03/13/facebook-instagram-and-messenger-are-down-for-some-users/ |website=TechCrunch |accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the number of monthly Telegram users as of October 2019 is 300 million people worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/complaints/2019/comp-pr2019-212.pdf|title=SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION,        ::Plaintiff,  :19 Civ. 9439(PKC):-against -:ECF Case:TELEGRAM GROUPINC.andTON ISSUERINC.,|last=|first=|date=October 11, 2019|website=The US Securities and Exchange Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Features ==\n\n=== Account ===\n[[File:Telegram account self-destruction.png|thumb|Account self-destruction]]\n[[File:Telegram account is limited.png|thumb|The user was [[Block (Internet)|limited]].]]\nTelegram accounts are tied to telephone numbers and are verified by [[Short Message Service|SMS]].<ref name=\"Lopez\">{{Citation|url=http://www.applesfera.com/aplicaciones-ios-1/configurando-telegram-en-el-iphone-en-la-web-y-en-el-mac|title=Configurando Telegram en el iPhone, en la web y en el Mac|first=Miguel|last=Lopez|trans-title=Configuring Telegram in the Apple iPhone, the Web and the Mac|language=es|publisher=Applesfera|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> Users can add multiple devices to their account and receive messages on each one. Connected devices can be removed individually or all at once. The associated number can be changed at any time and when doing so, the user's contacts will receive the new number automatically.<ref name=\"Lopez\" /><ref name=\"way-transf\">{{cite web|url = http://www.wayerless.com/2014/12/telegram-se-actualiza-permitiendo-ahora-migrar-tus-conversaciones-y-contactos-a-una-linea-nueva/|first = Jonathan|last = Munizaga|date = 1 December 2014|trans-title = Telegram already allows migrating conversations and contacts to a new line|title = Telegram ya permite migrar conversaciones y contactos a una l\u00ednea nueva|publisher = Wayerless|accessdate = 2 December 2014|language = es|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141219220850/http://www.wayerless.com/2014/12/telegram-se-actualiza-permitiendo-ahora-migrar-tus-conversaciones-y-contactos-a-una-linea-nueva/|archivedate = 19 December 2014|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"te-transf\">{{cite web|language = es|url = http://www.tuexpertoapps.com/2014/12/02/telegram-ahora-permite-traspasar-mensajes-al-cambiar-de-numero/|first = David G|last = Mateo|date = 1 December 2014|title = Telegram ahora permite traspasar mensajes al cambiar de n\u00famero|publisher = TuExperto|accessdate = 2 December 2014}}</ref> In addition, a user can set up an [[Pseudonym|alias]] that allows them to send and receive messages without exposing their phone number.<ref name=\"cs2.0\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/10/23/secure-messaging-app-telegram-adds-usernames-and-snapchat-like-hold-to-view-for-media/|title=Secure Messaging App Telegram Adds Usernames And Snapchat-Like Hold-To-View For Media|publisher=Techcrunch|date=23 October 2014|accessdate=23 October 2014}}</ref> Telegram accounts can be deleted at any time and they are deleted automatically after six months of inactivity by default, which can optionally be changed to 1 month and 12 months. Users can replace exact \"last seen\" timestamps with broader messages such as \"last seen recently\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Hiding Last Seen Time - Done Right|url=https://telegram.org/blog/privacy-revolution|accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe default method of [[authentication]] that Telegram uses for [[login]]s is SMS-based single-factor authentication.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kirk|first1=Jeremy|title=How much trust can you put in Telegram messenger?|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2871412/how-much-trust-can-you-put-in-telegram-messenger.html|website=PC World|publisher=IDG|accessdate=4 May 2016|date=15 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Rad-2015-01-09\"/> All that is needed in order to log into an account and gain access to that user's cloud-based messages is a one-time passcode that is sent via SMS to the user's phone number.<ref name=\"Rad-2015-01-09\">{{cite web|last1=Rad|first1=Alex|title=A 264 Attack On Telegram, And Why A Super Villain Doesn't Need It To Read Your Telegram Chats.|url=http://www.alexrad.me/discourse/a-264-attack-on-telegram-and-why-a-super-villain-doesnt-need-it-to-read-your-telegram-chats.html|website=alexrad.me|type=Blog|accessdate=4 May 2016|date=9 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425091011/http://www.alexrad.me/discourse/a-264-attack-on-telegram-and-why-a-super-villain-doesnt-need-it-to-read-your-telegram-chats.html|archivedate=25 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Lokot-2016-05-02\"/> These login SMS messages are known to have been intercepted in Iran, Russia and Germany, possibly in coordination with phone companies.<ref name=\"Lokot-2016-05-02\"/><ref name=\"Menn-2016-08-02\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lipp|first1=Sebastian|last2=Hoppenstedt|first2=Max|title=Exklusiv: Wie das BKA Telegram-Accounts von Terrorverd\u00e4chtigen knackt|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/de/read/exklusiv-wie-das-bka-telegram-accounts-von-terrorverdaechtigen-knackt|website=Motherboard|publisher=Vice Media Inc.|accessdate=28 August 2016|language=German|date=26 August 2016}}</ref> Pavel Durov has said that Telegram users in \"troubled countries\" should enable [[two-factor authentication]] by creating passwords, which Telegram allows, but does not require.<ref name=\"Lokot-2016-05-02\">{{cite web|last1=Lokot|first1=Tetyana|title=Is Telegram Really Safe for Activists Under Threat? These Two Russians Aren't So Sure.|url=https://advox.globalvoices.org/2016/05/02/is-telegram-really-safe-for-activists-under-threat-these-two-russians-arent-so-sure/|website=Advox|publisher=Global Voices|accessdate=4 May 2016|date=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Menn-2016-08-02\">{{cite news|last1=Menn|first1=Joseph|last2=Torbati|first2=Yeganeh|title=Exclusive: Hackers accessed Telegram messaging accounts in Iran - researchers|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iran-cyber-telegram-exclusive-idUSKCN10D1AM|accessdate=3 August 2016|work=Reuters|publisher=Thomson Reuters|date=2 August 2016|location=San Francisco/Washington}}</ref>\n\n=== Cloud-based messages ===\nTelegram's default messages are cloud-based and can be accessed on any of the user's connected devices. Users can share photos, videos, audio messages and other files (up to 1.5 [[gigabyte]] in size per file). Users can send messages to other users individually or to groups of up to 200,000 members.<ref name=\"Venture-5k\">{{cite news|url=https://twitter.com/telegram/status/922426780316774401|title=Group chats on Telegram can now have up to 1,00,000 members. Admins can use advanced permissions and butler bots to keep the peace.|date=23 October 2017|via=Twitter.com}}</ref> Sent messages can be edited within 48 hours after they have been sent and deleted at any time on both sides. This gives user an ability to correct typos and retract messages that were sent by mistake.<ref name=\"Telegram Unsend Messages\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/unsend-and-usage|publisher=Telegram|title=Unsend Messages, Network Usage, and More|date=3 January 2017|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> The transmission of messages to Telegram Messenger LLP's servers is encrypted with the service's [[MTProto]] protocol.<ref name=\"how-secure\" /> According to Telegram's privacy policy, \"all data is stored heavily encrypted and the encryption keys in each case are stored in several other DCs in different jurisdictions. This way local engineers or physical intruders cannot get access to user data\".<ref>{{cite web|title = Telegram Privacy Policy|url = https://telegram.org/privacy|website = Telegram|access-date = 17 January 2016}}</ref> This makes the messages' security roughly comparable to that of e-mail. Here, most providers employ client-server encryption as well, however usually with the standardized protocol [[Transport Layer Security]]. E-mails may or may not be encrypted on the servers. Telegram cloud messages and media remain on the servers at least until deleted by all participants.\n\n=== Bots ===\nIn June 2015, Telegram launched a platform for third-party developers to create [[IM bot|bots]].<ref name=\"Telegram Bot Platform\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/bot-revolution|publisher=Telegram|title=Telegram Bot Platform|date=24 June 2015|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref> Bots are Telegram accounts operated by programs. They can respond to messages or [[Mention (blogging)|mentions]], can be invited into groups and can be integrated into other programs. It also accepts online payments with credit cards and [[Apple Pay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/payments|title=Payments for Bots|website=Telegram|access-date=2018-02-12}}</ref> Dutch website ''[[Tweakers]]'' reported that an invited bot can potentially read all group messages when the bot controller changes the access settings silently at a later point in time. Telegram pointed out that it considered implementing a feature that would announce such a status change within the relevant group.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://tweakers.net/nieuws/104386/telegram-bots-kunnen-relatief-ongemerkt-meelezen-in-groepsgesprekken.html|title = Telegram-bots kunnen relatief ongemerkt meelezen in groepsgesprekken|date = 23 July 2015|accessdate = 25 October 2015|website = [[Tweakers]]|last = Schellevis|first = Joost|language = nl}}</ref> Also there are inline bots, which can be used from any chat screen. In order to activate an inline bot, user needs to type in the message field a bot's username and query. The bot then will offer its content. User can choose from that content and send it within a chat.<ref name=\"Inline Bots\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/inline-bots|publisher=Telegram|title=Introducing Inline Bots|date=4 January 2016|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Channels ===\nIn September 2015, Telegram added channels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/channels|title=Channels: Broadcasting Done Right|date=2015-09-22|website=Telegram|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> Channels are a form of one-way messaging where admins are able to post messages but other users are not. Any user is able to create and subscribe to channels. Channels can be created for broadcasting messages to an unlimited number of subscribers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lobao|first1=Martim|title=Telegram v3.2 Brings Channels For Broadcasting Your Messages To The World|url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2015/09/22/telegram-v3-2-brings-channels-broadcasting-messages-world/|work=Android Police|date=22 September 2015}}</ref> Channels can be publicly available with an alias and a permanent URL so anyone can join. Users who join a channel can see the entire message history. Users can join and leave channels at any time. Depending on a channel's settings, messages may be signed with the channel's name or with the username of the admin who posted them. Non-admin users are unable to see other users who've subscribed to the channel. Furthermore, users can mute a channel, meaning that the user will still receive messages, but won't be notified. Admins can give permission to post comments on the Telegram channel with help of bots. The admin of the channel can obtain general data about the channel. Each message has its own view counter, showing how many users have seen this message, this includes views from forwarded messages. As of May 2019, the creator of a channel can add a discussion group, a separate group where messages in the channel are automatically posted for subscribers to communicate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/privacy-discussions-web-bots|title=Focused Privacy, Discussion Groups, Seamless Web Bots and More|date=2019-05-31|website=Telegram|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] moved their messenger-based newsletter service from [[WhatsApp]] to Telegram after the former banned bulk and automated messaging.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-04/how-to-follow-bloomberg-on-telegram|title=How to Follow Bloomberg on Telegram|last=Hess|first=Megan|date=December 3, 2019|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Jan 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://digiday.com/media/bloomberg-news-using-telegram/|title=How Bloomberg News is using Telegram|last=Ting|first=Deanna|date=2020-01-10|website=Digiday|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> The news service is attempting to grow its audience outside the U.S.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n=== Stickers ===\n\nStickers are cloud-based, high-definition images intended to provide more expressive [[emoji]]. When typing in an emoji, the user is offered to send the respective sticker instead. Stickers come in collections called \"sets\", and multiple stickers can be offered for one emoji. Telegram comes with one default sticker set,<ref name=\"Telegram Stickers\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/stickers-meet-art-and-history|publisher=Telegram|title=Telegram Stickers|date=2 January 2015|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> but users can install additional sticker sets provided by third-party contributors. Sticker sets installed from one client become automatically available to all other clients. Sticker images use [[WebP]] file format, which is better optimized to be transmitted over internet.\n\n=== Drafts ===\n\nDrafts are unfinished messages synced across user devices. One can start typing a message on one device and continue on another. The draft will persist in editing area on any device until it is sent or removed.<ref name=\"Drafts\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/drafts|publisher=Telegram|title=Drafts, Picture-in-Picture, and More|date=14 June 2016|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Secret chats ===\n[[File:Telegram secret chat - en.png|thumb|200px|A \"secret chat\" confirmation notice - screenshot from [[Android Marshmallow]].]]\nMessages can also be sent with client-to-client encryption in so-called secret chats. These messages are encrypted with the service's [[MTProto]] protocol.<ref name=\"techfaq\" /> Unlike Telegram's cloud-based messages, messages sent within a secret chat can be accessed only on the device upon which the secret chat was initiated and the device upon which the secret chat was accepted; they cannot be accessed on other devices.<ref name=\"TechCrunch\" /><ref name=\"how-secure\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-how-secure-is-telegram|publisher=Telegram|work=FAQ|title=How secure is Telegram?}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|publisher=Telegram|url=https://core.telegram.org/mtproto|title=Description of MTProto Mobile Protocol}}</ref> Messages sent within secret chats can, in principle, be deleted at any time and can optionally self-destruct.<ref>{{harvnb|Rottermanner|Kieseberg|Huber|Schmiedecker|2015|p=2}}</ref>\n\nSecret chats have to be initiated and accepted by an invitation, upon which the encryption keys for the session are exchanged. Users in a secret chat can verify that no [[man-in-the-middle attack]] has occurred by comparing pictures that visualize their [[public key fingerprint]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hamburger|first1=Ellis|title=Why Telegram has become the hottest messaging app in the world|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/2/25/5445864/telegram-messenger-hottest-app-in-the-world|website=The Verge|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=17 March 2016|date=25 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Telegram, secret chats have supported [[perfect forward secrecy]] since December 2014. Encryption keys are periodically changed after a key has been used more than 100 times or has been in use for more than a week.<ref name=\"Rottermanner-2015-p6\">{{harvnb|Rottermanner|Kieseberg|Huber|Schmiedecker|2015|p=6}}</ref> Old encryption keys are destroyed.<ref name=\"way-transf\" /><ref name=\"te-transf\" /><ref>{{Citation|url=https://core.telegram.org/api/end-to-end/pfs|publisher=Telegram|title=Perfect Forward Secrecy|date=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nWindows and GNU/Linux users are still not able to use secret chats using the official Telegram Desktop app while the official macOS-only client supports them.<ref>{{cite web|title = Github issue 871: missing secret chats|url = https://github.com/telegramdesktop/tdesktop/issues/871|date = 2 July 2015|accessdate = 25 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nSecret chats are not available for groups or channels.\n\nTelegram's local message database is not encrypted by default.<ref name=\"Rottermanner-2015-p6\"/> Some Telegram clients allow users to encrypt the local message database by setting a passphrase.<ref name=\"zimperium\">{{cite news|last1=Franceschi-Bicchierai|first1=Lorenzo|title=Encryption Fails: When to Freak Out and When to Chill|url=http://motherboard.vice.com/read/encryption-fails-when-to-freak-out-and-when-to-chill|work=Motherboard|publisher=Vice Media|date=24 February 2015|accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Voice calls ===\nIn the end of March 2017, Telegram introduced its own [[voice call]]s. The calls are built upon the end-to-end encryption of Secret Chats. Connection is established as [[peer-to-peer]] whenever possible, otherwise the closest server to the client is used. According to Telegram, there is a [[Artificial neural network|neural network]] working to learn various technical parameters about a call to provide better quality of the service for future uses. After a brief initial trial in Western Europe, voice calls are now available for use in most countries.<ref name=\"Telegram Voice Calls\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/calls|publisher=Telegram|title=Voice Calls: Secure, Crystal-Clear, AI-Powered|date=30 March 2017|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Telescope (video messages) ===\nSince version 4.1, released in May 2017, Telegram offers a dedicated video hosting platform called Telescope.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/video-messages-and-telescope|title=Video Messages and Telescope|website=Telegram|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref> The round videos can be up to one minute long and autoplay. When posted in a public channel on Telegram, the videos are also uploaded to and viewable without an account. However, Telegram video messages and \"Telescope\" videos sent within non-public chats or groups are not published.\n\n=== Live locations ===\nFor either 15 minutes, one hour, or eight hours, Telegram users can share their live location in a chat since version 4.4 released in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/live-locations|title=Live Locations, Media Player and Languages|website=Telegram|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref> If multiple users share their live location within a group, they are shown on an interactive map. Sharing the 'live location' can be stopped at any time.\n\n=== Social login ===\nIn February 2018, Telegram launched their [[social login]] feature to its users, named as Telegram Login.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/login|title=Telegram Login for Websites|website=Telegram|access-date=2018-02-12}}</ref> It features a website widget that could be embedded into websites, allowing users to sign into a third party website with their Telegram account. The gateway sends users' Telegram name, username, and profile picture to the website owner, while users' phone number remains hidden. The gateway is integrated with a bot, which is linked with the developer's specific website domain.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.neowin.net/news/telegram-48-arrives-with-telegram-login-and-streaming|title=Telegram 4.8 arrives with Telegram Login and streaming|work=Neowin|access-date=2018-02-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Passport ===\nIn July 2018, Telegram introduced their [[online authorisation]] and [[identity management system]], Telegram Passport, for platforms that require real-life identification.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/passport|title=Introducing Telegram Passport|website=Telegram|access-date=2018-08-04}}</ref> It asks users to upload their own official documents such as passport, identity card, driver license, etc. When an online service requires such identification documents and verification, it forwards the information to the platform with the user's permission. Telegram stated that it does not have access to the data, while the platform will only share the information to the authorised recipient.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/07/27/telegram-passport/|title=Telegram Passport stores your real-world IDs in the cloud|work=Engadget|access-date=2018-08-04|language=en-US}}</ref> However, the service was criticised for being vulnerable to online [[Brute-force attack|brute force attacks]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/hardfork/2018/08/02/telegram-passport-passwords-crack/|title=Telegram Passport is already drawing fire for not being secure enough|last=Canellis|first=David|date=2018-08-02|work=Hard Fork {{!}} The Next Web|access-date=2018-08-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Polls ===\nPolls are a feature of Telegram that are currently available on Android, iOS and the desktop applications Polls have the option to be anonymous or visible. A user can enter multiple options into the poll. Quiz mode can also be enabled where a user can select the right answer for their poll and leave it to the group to guess. Quiz bots can also be added to track correct answers and even provide a global leaderboard<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/polls-2-0-vmq|title=Polls 2.0: Visible Votes, Multiple Answers, and Quiz Mode|date=2020-01-23|website=Telegram|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>.\n\n== Architecture ==\n\n=== Encryption scheme ===\n[[File:Explanation of secret chats (Telegram).png|thumb|200px|A simplified illustration of the MTProto encryption scheme.]]\nTelegram uses a [[symmetric encryption]] scheme called [[MTProto]]. The protocol was developed by [[Nikolai Durov]] and other developers at Telegram and is based on 256-bit symmetric [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES]] encryption, 2048-bit [[RSA (cryptosystem)|RSA]] encryption and [[Diffie\u2013Hellman key exchange]].<ref name=\"techfaq\">{{cite web|url = https://core.telegram.org/techfaq|title = FAQ for the Technically Inclined|website = Telegram|accessdate = 9 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Servers ===\nTelegram Messenger LLP has servers in a number of countries throughout the world to improve the response time of their service.<ref>{{cite web|trans-title=Telegram, the chat that competes with WhatsApp|place=[[Uruguay|UY]]|url=http://www.elpais.com.uy/vida-actual/que-telegram-chat-que-compite.html|work=El Pa\u00eds|title=Telegram, el chat que compite con Whatsapp|language=es|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> Telegram's server-side software is closed-source and proprietary. Pavel Durov has said that it would require a major architectural redesign of the server-side software to connect independent servers to the Telegram cloud.<ref>{{cite web|title = Pavel Durov, creador de Telegram: \"Ninguna aplicaci\u00f3n es 100% segura\"|url = http://www.eldiario.es/turing/moviles_y_tabletas/telegram-pavel_durov-entrevista-app-movil-seguridad_0_224677688.html|work = eldiario.es|date = 2 February 2014|accessdate = 12 February 2014|trans-title = Pavel Durov, creator of Telegram: \"No application is 100% safe\"|last = Rull|first = Antonio|language = es}}</ref>\n\n=== Client apps ===\nTelegram has various client apps, some developed by Telegram Messenger LLP and some by the community. Most of them are [[free and open-source]] and released under the [[GNU General Public License|GNU General Public Licence]] {{Nowrap|version 2}} or 3.\n\n'''Common specifications:'''\n\n* No cloud backup option for secret chat\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Platform(s) !! Official !! Source code license !! Support for secret chats !! Notes\n|-\n| Telegram || [[Android (operating system)|Android]] 2.3 or later || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv2 or later}}<ref name=Apps /><ref>{{cite web|author=DrKLO|url=https://github.com/DrKLO/Telegram|title=DrKLO/Telegram|website=GitHub|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> || {{Yes}} || Supports [[tablet computer|tablets]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsslash.com/n/2288-telegram-anleitung-so-benutzt-man-den-messenger|language=de|title=Telegram-Anleitung: So benutzt man den Messenger|publisher=Newsslash}}</ref> and [[Android Wear]] smart watches.<ref>{{cite web|language=es|trans-title=Telegram updated with Android Wear compatibility|url=http://sevilla.abc.es/mobility/noticia/android/noticias-android/telegram-se-actualiza-con-compatibilidad-para-android-wear/|title=Telegram se actualiza con compatibilidad para Android Wear|publisher=ABC|place=Sevilla|accessdate=7 December 2014}}</ref> Support synchronisation between multiple devices.\n|-\n| Telegram Messenger || [[iOS]] 9.0 or later, [[watchOS]] 5.0 or later || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv2 or later}}<ref name=Apps /><ref>{{cite web|author=peter-iakovlev|url=https://github.com/peter-iakovlev/Telegram|title=peter-iakovlev/Telegram|website=GitHub|date=18 November 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> || {{Yes}} || Launched in August 2013 for [[iPhone]] and [[iPod Touch]] and relaunched in July 2014 with support for [[iPad]] and [[Apple Watch]].<ref>{{cite web|language=es|url=https://www.cnet.com/es/noticias/telegram-se-actualiza-para-la-pantalla-del-ipad/|trans-title=Telegram updates for the iPad screen|title=Telegram se actualiza para la pantalla del iPad|publisher=Cnet}}</ref>\n|-\n|Telegram X ||[[Android (operating system)|Android]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=cpy|first1=Mujeeb|title=Telegram X for Android Released \u2013 What\u2019s New\n|url=https://ibcomputing.com/telegram-x-for-android-released/ |website=IB Computing|publisher=IB Computing|accessdate=23 January 2018|language=English|date=23 January 2018}}</ref>|| {{yes}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Telegram X: Progress through Competition|url=https://telegram.org/blog/telegram-x|website=telegram.org|publisher=Telegram LLC}}</ref> || {{Proprietary}} || {{yes}} || An alternative Telegram client written from scratch, with higher speed, slicker animations, themes and more efficient battery use.\niOS version is written with [[Swift (programming language)|Swift]]. Android version based on TDLib.\nThe iOS version was discontinued, with its code merged with the main Telegram app.\n|-\n| Telegram Messenger || [[Windows Phone]] || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv2 or later}}<ref name=Apps>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/apps|website=Telegram.org|title=Telegram Apps|accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref> || {{Yes}} || Provide synchronization between all platforms\n|-\n| Telegram || [[Firefox OS]] || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv3}}<ref name=\"gh-webogram\">{{cite web|author=Igor Zhukov|url=https://github.com/zhukov/webogram|title=zhukov/webogram|website=GitHub|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref>|| {{No}} || Based on Webogram.\n|-\n| Telegram Desktop || [[Windows]], [[macOS]], and [[GNU/Linux]] || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv3 with OpenSSL exception}}<ref>{{cite web|author=telegramdesktop|url=https://github.com/telegramdesktop/tdesktop|title=telegramdesktop/tdesktop|website=GitHub|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> || {{no}} || Qt-based desktop client. The Windows client is a traditional desktop app published in three flavors:\nWith installer, portable, [[Windows Store app]].\n|-\n| Telegram || [[macOS]] || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv2}}<ref>{{cite web|author=overtake|url=https://github.com/overtake/telegram|title=overtake/telegram|website=GitHub|date=1 December 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> || {{yes}} ||Native macOS client.\n|-\n| Telegram || [[Google Chrome]] and [[Chrome OS]] || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv3}}<ref name=\"gh-webogram\" />|| {{No}} ||Based on Webogram, published on the [[Chrome Web Store]].\n|-\n| Telegram CLI<ref name=\"Lokot-2016-05-02\" /><ref name=\"tg-cli\" /> || [[GNU/Linux]], [[FreeBSD]] and [[macOS]] || {{No}}<ref name=Apps /> || {{free|GPLv2}}<ref name=\"tg-cli\">{{cite web|author=vysheng|url=https://github.com/vysheng/tg|title=vysheng/tg|website=GitHub|accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref> || {{Yes}} || Command-line interface for Telegram.\n|-\n|Unigram<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/store/p/unigram-preview/9n97zckpd60q|title=Unigram Preview - Microsoft Store|website=Microsoft Store|language=en-us|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/UnigramDev/Unigram|title=UnigramDev/Unigram|website=GitHub|language=en|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref> || [[Windows 10]], [[Windows 10 Mobile]] || {{No}}<ref name=Apps /> || {{Free|GPLv3}} || {{Yes}} || A [[Universal Windows Platform app]] published on the [[Microsoft Store]].\n|-\n| Telegram{{third-party inline|date=April 2016}} || [[Ubuntu Touch]] || {{no}} || {{free|GPLv2}}<ref name=\"ubuntu-telegram-app\">{{cite web|url=https://launchpad.net/telegram-app|title=Telegram app|website=Launchpad}}</ref> || {{Yes}} ||Based on TelegramQML.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://launchpad.net/telegram-app|title=Telegram App in Launchpad|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n| Sailorgram{{third-party inline|date=April 2016}}||[[Sailfish OS]]|| {{no}} || {{free|GPLv3}}<ref name=\"Sailfish Telegram App\">{{cite web|url=https://openrepos.net/content/dax/sailorgram|title=Telegram app|website=OpenRepos}}</ref> || {{Yes}} || Based on Cutegram which based on [[Qt (software)|Qt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aseman.co/en/products/cutegram/|title=Cutegram|author=Aseman Land|publisher=Aseman|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> \n|-\n| Telegram-FOSS || [[Android (operating system)|Android]] 2.3 or later || {{no}} || {{free|GPLv2 or later}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/Telegram-FOSS-Team/Telegram-FOSS|title=Unofficial, FOSS-friendly fork of the original Telegram client for Android: Telegram-FOSS-Team/Telegram-FOSS|date=6 August 2019|via=GitHub}}</ref>|| {{Yes}} || Fork of official android version replacing non-FOSS components with equivalent FOSS ones.\n|-\n| telega.el || [[Emacs|Emacs]] || {{no}} || {{free|GPLv3 or later}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/zevlg/telega.el|title=Unofficial, Telegram client for Emacs|date=6 August 2019|via=GitHub}}</ref>|| {{Yes}} || telega.el is built on top of the official library provided by Telegram: tdlib[https://core.telegram.org/tdlib]. Available as MELPA and GUIX packages.\n|}\nUsers can also access Telegram's cloud-based messages via an official [[JavaScript]] [[web browser]] interface called Telegram Web (aka Webogram). Users can share images, files and [[emoji]]s with previously-added contacts; this works in most modern browsers, such as [[Firefox]], [[Safari (web browser)|Safari]], and [[Google Chrome]].<ref name=Apps /><ref name=\"gh-webogram\" />\n\n=== APIs ===\nTelegram has public [[Application programming interface|APIs]] with which developers can access the same functionality as Telegram's official apps to build their own messaging applications.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.programmableweb.com/news/can-telegram-beat-whatsapp-public-api/2014/03/03|title=Can Telegram Beat WhatsApp with a Public API?|last=Roble|first=Patricio|date=3 March 2014|work=ProgrammableWeb}}</ref> In February 2015, creators of the unofficial Whatsapp+ client released the Telegram Plus app, later renamed to Plus Messenger, after their original project got a [[Cease and desist|cease-and-desist order]] from [[WhatsApp]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2015/02/27/whatsapp-developer-releases-telegram-forced-drop-first-project/|title=WhatsApp+ Developer Releases Telegram+ After Being Forced To Drop The First Project|last=King|first=Bertel|date=27 February 2015|work=AndroidPolice}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2015/01/21/whatsapp-now-officially-dead-receiving-cease-desist-real-whatsapp/|title=WhatsApp+ Is Now Officially Dead After Receiving A Cease And Desist From The Real WhatsApp|date=21 January 2015|website=Android Police|access-date=}}</ref> In September 2015, [[Samsung]] released a messaging application based on these APIs.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://news.samsung.com/global/socializer-messenger-app-offers-a-new-approach-to-messaging|title = Socializer Messenger App Offers a New Approach to Messaging|date = 14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nTelegram also offers an API that allows developers to create [[IM bot|bots]], which are accounts controlled by programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.programmableweb.com/news/telegram-launches-bot-api-and-platform/2015/06/29|title=Telegram Launches Bot API and Platform|last=Carter|first=Eric|date=27 June 2015|website=ProgrammableWeb}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/24/telegrams-new-platform-lets-developers-create-smart-message-bots-with-multiple-uses/|title=Telegram\u2019s New Platform Lets Developers Create Smart Message Bots With Multiple Uses|last=Butcher|first=Mike|date=24 June 2015|website=TechCrunch}}</ref> In February 2016, ''[[Forbes]]'' launched an [[Artificial intelligence|AI]]-powered news bot that pushes popular stories to subscribers and replies to search queries with relevant articles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bruceupbin/2016/02/23/introducing-the-forbes-newsbot-on-telegram/#270d46ef3117|title=Introducing The Forbes Newsbot on Telegram|last=Ubpin|first=Bruce|date=23 February 2016|website=Forbes}}</ref> [[TechCrunch]] launched a similar bot in March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/03/15/check-out-the-new-ai-powered-techcrunch-news-bot-on-telegram-messenger/|title=Check out the new AI-powered TechCrunch news bot on Telegram messenger|last=Bernard|first=Travis|date=15 March 2016|website=TechCrunch}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Security ===\n\nTelegram's security model has received notable criticism by cryptography experts. They criticized the general security model of permanently storing all contacts, messages and media together with their decryption keys on its servers by default and by not enabling [[end-to-end encryption]] for messages by default.<ref name=\"cpj-2016-05-31\"/><ref name=\"Turton-2016-06-24\">{{cite web|last1=Turton|first1=William|title=Why You Should Stop Using Telegram Right Now|url=https://gizmodo.com/why-you-should-stop-using-telegram-right-now-1782557415|website=Gizmodo|publisher=Gawker Media|accessdate=7 July 2016|date=24 June 2016}}</ref> [[Pavel Durov]] has argued that this is because it helps to avoid third-party unsecure backups, and to allow users to access messages and files from any device.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Durov|first=Pavel|url=http://telegra.ph/Why-Isnt-Telegram-End-to-End-Encrypted-by-Default-08-14|title=Why Isn't Telegram End-to-End Encrypted by Default?|date=2017-08-14|work=Telegraph|access-date=2017-10-01}}</ref> Cryptography experts have furthermore criticized Telegram's use of a custom-designed encryption protocol that has not been proven reliable and secure.<ref name=\"cpj-2016-05-31\" /><ref name=\"Jakobsen 2015\">{{harvnb|Jakobsen|Orlandi|2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Cox-2015\">{{cite web|last1=Cox|first1=Joseph|title=Why You Don't Roll Your Own Crypto|url=http://motherboard.vice.com/read/why-you-dont-roll-your-own-crypto|website=Motherboard|publisher=[[Vice Media]]|accessdate=11 December 2015|date=10 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"dailydot.com\">{{cite web|last1=Turton|first1=William|title=Cryptography expert casts doubt on encryption in ISIS' favorite messaging app|url=http://www.dailydot.com/politics/telegram-isis-encryption-cryptography/|website=The Daily Dot|accessdate=11 December 2015|date=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nCryptography experts have expressed both doubts and criticisms on Telegram's [[MTProto]] encryption scheme, saying that deploying [[Snake oil (cryptography)|home-brewed and unproven cryptography]] may render the encryption vulnerable to bugs that potentially undermine its security, due to a lack of scrutiny.<ref name=\"cpj-2016-05-31\" /><ref name=\"Jakobsen 2015\"/><ref name=\"Cox-2015\"/> It has also been suggested that Telegram did not employ developers with sufficient expertise or credibility in this field.<ref name=\"dailydot.com\"/>\n\nCritics have also disputed claims by Telegram that it is \"more secure than mass market messengers like WhatsApp and [[Line (application)|Line]]\",<ref name=\"how-secure\"/> because WhatsApp applies end-to-end encryption to all of its traffic by default and uses the [[Signal Protocol]], which has been \"reviewed and endorsed by leading security experts\", while Telegram does neither and insecurely stores all messages, media and contacts in their cloud.<ref name=\"cpj-2016-05-31\"/><ref name=\"Turton-2016-06-24\"/> Since July 2016, Line has also applied end-to-end encryption to all of its messages by default.<ref name=\"Sawers-2016-06-30\">{{cite web|last1=Sawers|first1=Paul|title=Ahead of IPO, mobile messaging giant Line introduces end-to-end encryption by default|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/06/30/ahead-of-ipo-mobile-messaging-giant-line-introduces-end-to-end-encryption-by-default/|website=VentureBeat|accessdate=10 September 2016|date=30 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February 2014, the [[Germany|German]] [[consumer organization]] [[Stiftung Warentest]] evaluated several data-protection aspects of Telegram, along with other popular instant-messaging clients. Among the aspects considered were: the security of the data transmission, the service's terms of use, the accessibility of the source code and the distribution of the app. Telegram was rated 'critical' (''{{Lang|de|kritisch}}'') overall. The organization was favorable to Telegram's secure chats and partially open source code, but criticized the mandatory transfer of contact data to Telegram's servers and the lack of an imprint or address on the service's website. It noted that while the message data is encrypted on the device, it could not analyse the transmission due to a lack of source code.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.test.de/WhatsApp-und-Alternativen-Datenschutz-im-Test-4675013-0/|title=WhatsApp und Alternativen: Datenschutz im Test|date=26 February 2014|website=[[Stiftung Warentest]]|language=de|trans-title=WhatsApp and alternatives: data protection tested|access-date=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] (EFF) listed Telegram on its \"Secure Messaging Scorecard\" in February 2015. Telegram's default chat function received a score of 4 out of 7 points on the scorecard. It received points for having communications encrypted in transit, having its code open to independent review, having the security design properly documented, and having completed a recent independent security audit. Telegram's default chat function missed points because the communications were not encrypted with keys the provider didn't have access to, users could not verify contacts' identities, and past messages were not secure if the encryption keys were stolen. Telegram's optional secret chat function, which provides end-to-end encryption, received a score of 7 out of 7 points on the scorecard.<ref name=\"EFF-scorecard-v1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/node/82654 |title=Secure Messaging Scorecard |date=17 February 2015|website=Electronic Frontier Foundation |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> The EFF said that the results \"should not be read as endorsements of individual tools or guarantees of their security\", and that they were merely indications that the projects were \"on the right track\".<ref name=\"EFF-scorecard-v1\"/>\n\nIn December 2015, two researchers from [[Aarhus University]] published a report in which they demonstrated that [[MTProto]] does not achieve [[Ciphertext indistinguishability#Indistinguishability under chosen ciphertext attack/adaptive chosen ciphertext attack (IND-CCA1, IND-CCA2)|indistinguishability under chosen-ciphertext attack]] (IND-CCA) or [[authenticated encryption]].<ref>{{harvnb|Jakobsen|Orlandi|2015|p=6}}</ref> The researchers stressed that the attack was of a theoretical nature and they \"did not see any way of turning the attack into a full plaintext-recovery attack\". Nevertheless, they said they saw \"no reason why [Telegram] should use a less secure encryption scheme when more secure (and at least as efficient) solutions exist\".<ref name=\"Jakobsen-2015-p1\">{{harvnb|Jakobsen|Orlandi|2015|p=1}}</ref> The Telegram team responded that the flaw does not affect message security<ref>{{cite web|title=FAQ for the Technically Inclined: What about IND-CCA?|url=https://core.telegram.org/techfaq#what-about-ind-cca|website=Telegram|publisher=Telegram|accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref> and that \"a future patch would address the concern\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Clary|first1=Grayson|title=The Flaw in ISIS's Favorite Messaging App|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2016/01/isiss-favorite-messaging-app-has-a-security-problem/422460/|website=The Atlantic|publisher=The Atlantic|accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref> Telegram 4.6, released in December 2017, supports [[MTProto]] 2.0, which now satisfied the conditions for IND-CCA.<ref name=\"Turton-2016-06-24\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=FAQ for the Technically Inclined|url=https://core.telegram.org/techfaq#what-about-ind-cca|website=Telegram|publisher=Telegram|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref> [[MTProto]] 2.0 is seen by qualified cryptographers as a vast improvement to Telegram's security.<ref name=\"Turton-2016-06-24\" />\n\nIn April 2016, accounts of several Russian opposition members were hijacked by intercepting the SMS messages used for login authorization.<ref name=\"Lokot-2016-05-02\"/> In response, Telegram recommended using the optional two-factor authentication feature.<ref name=\"Lokot-2016-05-02\"/> In May 2016, the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] and [[Nate Cardozo]], senior staff attorney at Electronic Frontier Foundation, recommended against using Telegram because of \"its lack of end-to-end encryption [by default] and its use of non-standard MTProto encryption protocol, which has been publicly criticized by cryptography researchers, including [[Matthew D. Green|Matthew Green]]\".<ref name=\"cpj-2016-05-31\">{{cite web|title=Why Telegram's security flaws may put Iran's journalists at risk|url=https://cpj.org/blog/2016/05/why-telegrams-security-flaws-may-put-irans-journal.php|publisher=Committee to Protect Journalists|accessdate=20 July 2016|date=31 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Pavel Durov claimed publicly that U.S. intelligence agencies tried to bribe the company's developers to weaken Telegram's encryption or install a backdoor during their visit to the U.S. in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Telegram founder: U.S. intelligence agencies tried to bribe us to weaken encryption|url=https://news.fastcompany.com/telegram-founder-us-intelligence-agencies-tried-to-bribe-us-to-weaken-encryption-4040876|accessdate=15 June 2017|work=FastCo News|date=15 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Leyden|first1=John|title=Telegram chat app founder claims Feds offered backdoor bribe|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2017/06/14/telegram_boss_backdoor_offer_claim/|website=The Register|publisher=Situation Publishing|accessdate=15 June 2017|date=14 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Telegram sent a message to all Iranian users stating Telegram Talai and Hotgram unofficial clones are not secure.<ref>{{Citation|title=\u0647\u0634\u062f\u0627\u0631 \u062a\u0644\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u062f\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0646\u0627\u0627\u0645\u0646 \u0628\u0648\u062f\u0646 \"\u0647\u0627\u062a\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645\" \u0648 \"\u0637\u0644\u0627\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645\"|url=https://www.radiofarda.com/a/iran-messaging-apps-security-concerns/29661203.html|language=fa|access-date=2019-01-18}}</ref>\n\nTelegram promised since at least March 2014 that \"all code will be released eventually\", including all the various client applications (Android, iOS, desktop, etc.) and the server-side code.<ref>{{cite web |title=Telegram F.A.Q. |url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-why-not-open-source-everything |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309205427/https://telegram.org/faq#q-why-not-open-source-everything |archivedate=2014-03-09 |website=web.archive.org |accessdate=21 January 2019 |date=9 March 2014}}</ref> As of February 2020, Telegram still hasn't published their server-side source code.<ref>{{cite web |title=Telegram F.A.Q. |url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-why-not-open-source-everything |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114013309/https://telegram.org/faq#q-why-not-open-source-everything |archivedate=2019-01-14 |website=web.archive.org |accessdate=21 January 2019 |date=14 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=r/Telegram - I think it's time for Telegram to release its server-side source code |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/Telegram/comments/a5l6hm/i_think_its_time_for_telegram_to_release_its/ |website=reddit |accessdate=21 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn June 9, 2019, [[The Intercept]] released leaked Telegram messages exchanged between current Brazilian Minister of Justice and former judge S\u00e9rgio Moro and federal prosecutors.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theintercept.com/series/secret-brazil-archive/ |title=Secret Brazil Archive \u2014 An Investigative Series by The Intercept |website=The Intercept |language=en |access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> The hypothesis is that either mobile devices were hacked by [[SIM swap scam|SIM swap]] or computers invaded.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/tecnologia/noticias/redacao/2019/06/10/como-hackers-tiveram-acesso-a-conversas-privadas-de-sergio-moro.htm |title=Como hackers tiveram acesso a conversas privadas de Sergio Moro? |website=noticias.uol.com.br |language=pt-br |access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> The Telegram team tweeted that it was either because the user had malware or they were not using [[Multi-factor authentication|2-step verification]].<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1138430205343731712 |user=telegram |title=Indeed, there's no evidence of any hack. Most likely to have been either malware or someone not using a 2-step verification password. |date=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 12, 2019, Telegram confirmed that it suffered a [[Denial-of-service attack]] which disrupted normal app functionality for approximately one hour. [[Pavel Durov]] tweeted that the [[IP address]]es used in the attack mostly came from China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-48619804|title=Telegram founder links cyber attack to China|date=2019-06-13|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019 media wrote about a numerous Telegram account takeovers of Russian businessmen that involved bypass of SMS second factor authentication. Takeover of Telegram account was also offered on dark web forums for $4000. Group-IB security company suggested [[Signalling System No. 7|SS7]] mobile signalling protocol weaknesses, illegal usage of surveillance equipment or telecom insider attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomasbrewster/2019/12/12/mystery-russian-telegram-hacks-intercept-secret-codes-to-spy-on-messages/|title=Mystery Russian Telegram Hacks Intercept Secret Codes To Spy On Messages|last=Brewster|first=Thomas|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvrain.ru/news/group_ib_rossijskie_predprinimateli_pozhalovalis_na_vzlom_perepiski_v_telegram-498660/|title=Group-IB: \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0436\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0437\u043b\u043e\u043c \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0432 Telegram|last=Inc|first=TV Rain|date=2019-12-04|website=tvrain.ru|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Cryptography contests ===\nTelegram has organized two cryptography contests to challenge its own security. Third parties were asked to break the service's cryptography and disclose the information contained within a secret chat between two computer-controlled users. A reward of respectively {{US$|200000}} and {{US$|300000}} was offered. Both of these contests expired with no winners.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://telegram.org/blog/winter-contest-ends|title = Winter Contest Ends|date = 2 March 2014|accessdate = 24 October 2015|website = Telegram}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://telegram.org/blog/cryptocontest-ends|title = Crypto Contest Ends|date = 11 February 2015|accessdate = 24 October 2015|website = Telegram}}</ref> Security researcher [[Moxie Marlinspike]] and commenters on ''[[Hacker News]]'' criticized the first contest for being rigged or framed in Telegram's favor and said that Telegram's statements on the value of these contests as proof of the cryptography's quality are misleading.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://thoughtcrime.org/blog/telegram-crypto-challenge/|archive-url = https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20140307220634/http://thoughtcrime.org/blog/telegram-crypto-challenge/|url-status=dead|archive-date = 7 March 2014|title = A Crypto Challenge for the Telegram Developers|first = Moxie|last = Marlinspike|date = 19 December 2013|work = Thought Crime|accessdate = 2 March 2014|authorlink = Moxie Marlinspike|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://tech.eu/news/telegram-protocol-cracking-contest/|title = Cracking contest: first one who breaks Telegram gets $200,000 in bitcoins (but really, nobody wins)|first = Robin|last = Wauters|date = 19 December 2013|accessdate = 2 March 2014|website = Tech.eu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.cryptofails.com/post/70546720222/telegrams-cryptanalysis-contest|title = Telegram's Cryptanalysis Contest|date = 19 December 2013|accessdate = 24 October 2015|website = Crypto Fails|last = Hornby|first = Taylor}}</ref>\n\n=== Censorship ===\n\nCountries blocking Telegram:\n{{Highlighted world map by country |CN=#8E0000 | RU=#D34343 | IR=#D34343  | IN=#D34343 }}\n{{legend|#8E0000|Completely blocked|border=1px #555 solid}}\n{{legend|#D34343|Partially blocked (some ISPs or audio traffic)|border=1px #555 solid}}\n\n\n==== Iran ==== \n{{main|Telegram in Iran}}\n\n\nTelegram was open and working in Iran without any VPN or other circumvention methods in May 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tasnimnews.com/fa/news/1394/02/21/736788/%D8%AA%D9%84%DA%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%85-%D9%81%DB%8C%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1-%D9%86%D8%B4%D8%AF%D9%87-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA |publisher=Tasnim News Agency|location=Tehran|quote=Though it is claimed by many that the Telegram is banned, but it is operating normally in Iran.|date=11 May 2015|accessdate=29 October 2015|title=\u062a\u0644\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u06cc\u0644\u062a\u0631 \u0646\u0634\u062f\u0647 \u0627\u0633\u062a|language=fa}}</ref> In August 2015, the [[Ministry of Information and Communications Technology of Iran|Iranian Ministry of ICT]] asserted that Telegram had agreed to restrict some of its bots and sticker packs in Iran at the request of the Iranian government.<ref name=\"globalvoices-08-2015\" /> According to an article published on ''[[Global Voices Online|Global Voices]]'', these features were being used by Iranians to \"share satirical comments about the Iranian government\". The article also noted that \"some users are concerned that Telegram's willingness to comply with Iranian government requests might mean future complicity with other Iranian government censorship, or even allow government access to Telegram's data on Iranian users\".<ref name=\"globalvoices-08-2015\">{{cite web|last1=Alimardani|first1=Mahsa|title=Is Telegram's Compliance with Iran Compromising the Digital Security of Its Users?|url=https://advocacy.globalvoicesonline.org/2015/08/28/is-telegrams-compliance-with-iran-compromising-the-digital-security-of-its-users/|publisher=Global Voices Online|accessdate=30 August 2015|date=28 August 2015}}</ref> Telegram has stated that all Telegram chats are private territory and that they do not process any requests related to them. Only requests regarding public content (bots and sticker packs) will be processed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-there-39s-illegal-content-on-telegram-how-do-i-take-it-down|publisher=Telegram|title=Telegram FAQ|accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref> In May 2016, the Iranian government asked all messaging apps, including Telegram, to move all Iranian users' data to Iranian servers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/05/30/iran-forces-messaging-apps-to-move-data-to-iranian-servers/|title=Iran forces messaging apps to move data to Iranian servers|last=Dillet|first=Romain|website=TechCrunch|access-date=31 May 2016}}</ref> On 20 April 2017, the Iranian government completely blocked Telegram's new voice calls, a service that allows individuals to make calls via secure, end-to-end encryption, and keep their conversations private.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iranhumanrights.org/2017/04/iranian-judiciary-blocks-popular-telegram-apps-new-voice-call-service/|title=Iranian Judiciary Blocks Popular Telegram App\u2019s New Voice Call Service \u2013 Center for Human Rights in Iran|website=www.iranhumanrights.org|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 30, 2017, during [[2017\u201318 Iranian protests|anti-government demonstrations across Iran]], Telegram has shut down a channel of the Iranian opposition that published calls to use Molotov cocktails against the police, after receiving a complaint from the Iranian government. Pavel Durov explained that the reason for the blocking was a \"no calls to violence\" policy and confirmed that criticizing local authorities, challenging the status quo and engaging in political debate were seen as \"OK\" by the platform, while \"promoting violence\" was not.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.recode.net/2017/12/30/16833542/telegram-iran-demostrations-messaging-protests-pavel-durov|title=\"Telegram is shutting down a channel that called for violent protests against Iran\u2019s government\"| date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> The opposition group promised to comply with Telegram rules and created a new channel which amassed 700,000 subscribers in less than 24 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/durov/status/947422726322565121| title=Twitter conversation between Nariman Gharib and Pavel Durov| date= December 31, 2017}}</ref> On December, 31, the Iranian government announced that Telegram has been \"temporarily restricted\" in order to \"ensure calm and security\" after the company said it refused to shut down peaceful protesting channels.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/12/31/middleeast/iran-protests-sunday/index.html|title=\"Iran restricts social media and issues stern warning to protesters\"|date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> On January, 13, the app was unblocked by an order of the president [[Hassan Rouhani]], who said that \"more than 100,000 jobs had been lost\u201d in Iran as a result of the ban on Telegram. Channels of the opposition remain operational.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iranhumanrights.org/2018/01/iran-unblocks-widely-used-messaging-app-telegram-after-two-weeks/|title=Iran Unblocks Widely Used Messaging App Telegram After Two Weeks \u2013 Center for Human Rights in Iran|website=www.iranhumanrights.org|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Iran's chairman for the Committee for Foreign policy and National Security [[Alaeddin Boroujerdi]] announced that Telegram has been targeted to be fully blocked in Iran by 20 April 2018,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://irinn.ir/fa/news/579406/%D8%A8%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%AC%D8%B1%D8%AF%DB%8C-%D8%AA%D9%84%DA%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%85-%D8%A8%D9%87-%D8%B2%D9%88%D8%AF%DB%8C-%D9%81%DB%8C%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1-%D9%85%DB%8C-%D8%B4%D9%88%D8%AF|title=\n\u0628\u0631\u0648\u062c\u0631\u062f\u06cc: \u062a\u0644\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0628\u0647 \u0632\u0648\u062f\u06cc \u0641\u06cc\u0644\u062a\u0631 \u0645\u06cc \u0634\u0648\u062f|date=2018-03-31|access-date=2018-03-31|language=en-US}}</ref> citing Telegram's role in facilitating the winter protests and the need to promote local apps.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2018/04/iran-telegram-block-filtering-protests-boroujerdi-soroush.html|title=Is Iran ready to block Telegram?|last=Staff|first=Al-Monitor|date=2018-04-02|work=Al-Monitor|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-us}}</ref> President Rouhani agreed with the need to break Telegram's monopoly in Iran, but maintained that he was opposed to a new blockade and did not see it as an effective measure to promote local apps.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2018/04/iran-telegram-block-filtering-rouhani-jahromi-opposition.html|title=Rouhani administration pushes back against Telegram blocking|last=Staff|first=Al-Monitor|date=2018-04-03|work=Al-Monitor|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-us}}</ref> Iranian MP [[Mahmoud Sadeghi]] noted that during the two weeks that Telegram was blocked in January 2018, 30 million Iranians (75% of Telegram's users in Iran) did not start using local messaging apps, but instead turned to VPN services to circumvent the block, rendering the blockade ineffective.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iranhumanrights.org/2018/04/iran-poised-to-block-popular-telegram-messaging-app-but-lacks-feasible-alternative/|title=Iran Poised to Block Popular Telegram Messaging App But Lacks Feasible Alternative \u2013 Center for Human Rights in Iran|website=www.iranhumanrights.org|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref>\n\nSince the end of the riots, the Iranian government employs a customized version of Telegram that is under their domain.<ref>{{Citation|title=\u0647\u0634\u062f\u0627\u0631 \u062a\u0644\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u062f\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0646\u0627\u0627\u0645\u0646 \u0628\u0648\u062f\u0646 \"\u0647\u0627\u062a\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645\" \u0648 \"\u0637\u0644\u0627\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645\"|url=https://www.radiofarda.com/a/iran-messaging-apps-security-concerns/29661203.html|language=fa|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 2019, Bijan Ghasemzadeh, the Iranian prosecutor who ordered the block on Telegram, was arrested for charges of corruption. It is unclear whether or not the charges were related to the ban on Telegram.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/fd6cbede80b94bbd8f7c950f6bfc2920|title=Iran arrests prosecutor behind ban on popular messaging app|date=2019-10-01|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n==== China ====\n\n\nIn July 2015, it was reported that China blocked access to Telegram Messenger. According to state-owned ''[[People's Daily]]'', Chinese human rights lawyers used Telegram to criticize the [[Chinese Government]] and the [[Communist Party of China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2015/07/13/china-blocks-telegram-messenger-blamed-for-aiding-human-rights-lawyers/|title=China blocks Telegram messenger, blamed for aiding human rights lawyers - Hong Kong Free Press HKFP|date=13 July 2015|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn August 28, 2019 the Hong Kong Internet Service Providers Association announced that the Hong Kong government had plans to block Telegram.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hkispa.org.hk/139-urgent-statement-of-hkispa-on-selective-blocking-of-internet-services.html |title=Urgent Statement of HKISPA on Selective Blocking of Internet Services |date=28 August 2019 |website=hkispa.org.hk |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Bahrain====\n\n\nIn June 2016, it was found that some ISPs in [[Bahrain]] had started to block Telegram.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bahrainwatch.org/blog/2016/06/28/leading-bahraini-isps-are-blocking-telegram-traffic/|title=Leading Bahraini ISPs are Blocking Telegram Traffic|date=2016-06-28|work=Bahrain Watch|access-date=2017-08-08|language=en-US}}</ref> In June 2017 the service faced serious pressure from Russian regulator [[Roscomnadzor]], who tried to force Telegram to register in the official telecommunication services registry, which implies serious liability for a registered party. After week-long negotiations and seeming imminent blockage of the service, the conflict ceased after high officials pulled some strings with the regulator.{{clarify|date=April 2018}} \n\n==== Indonesia ====\n\n\nOn 14 July 2017, eleven domain name servers related to Telegram were banned by the [[Indonesia]]n Communication and Information Ministry with the possibility of closing all Telegram applications in Indonesia if Telegram did not make a standard operating procedure to maintain content that was considered unlawful in the apps.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.riaupos.co/print.php?cat=11&id=156454 |title=Tak Perlu Blokir Telegram, Pengamat Sarankan Cara Ini kepada Mekominfo |author=Boy Riza Utama |date=July 15, 2017}}</ref> In August 2017, Indonesian Government has opened full access of Telegram, after Telegram has made self censorship about negative contents mainly radicalism and terrorism. Telegram said that about 10 channels/groups have been deleted from Telegram everyday due to are categorized as negative contents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tribunnews.com/nasional/2017/08/10/telegram-setiap-hari-hapus-10-grup-di-indonesia-terkait-konten-radikal-dan-terorisme |title=Telegram Setiap Hari Hapus 10 Grup Di Indonesia Terkait Konten Radikal dan Terorisme |date=August 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Pakistan ====\n\n\nIn October 2017, Telegram was inaccessible to users in Pakistan,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://propakistani.pk/2017/10/24/telegram-secure-alternative-whatsapp-pakistan/|title=Telegram, the Secure Alternative to Whatsapp, is Down in Pakistan|date=2017-10-24|access-date=2017-11-18|language=en-US}}</ref> and as of 17 November 2017, it has been completely blocked as per instructions from [[Pakistan Telecommunication Authority|PTA]], Pakistan's largest ISP, [[Ptcl|PTCL]] mentioned this in a tweet to a user.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://propakistani.pk/2017/11/17/telegram-blocked-pakistan/|title=Telegram Blocked in Pakistan!|date=2017-11-17|access-date=2017-11-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==== Russia ==== \n{{main|Blocking Telegram in Russia}}\n\n\nOn 13 April 2018, Telegram was banned in Russia by a Moscow court, due to its refusal to grant the [[Federal Security Service]] (FSB) access to encryption keys needed to view user communications as required by federal anti-terrorism law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/apr/13/moscow-court-bans-telegram-messaging-app|title=Moscow court bans Telegram messaging app|last=Roth|first=Andrew|date=2018-04-13|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=MacFarquhar|first1=Neil|title=Russian Court Bans Telegram App After 18-Minute Hearing|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/13/world/europe/russia-telegram-encryption.html?rref=collection%2Fsectioncollection%2Fbusiness|accessdate=13 April 2018|work=The New York Times|date=13 April 2018}}</ref> The ban has been enforced by blocking over 19 million [[IP address]]es associated with the service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/19/russias-game-of-telegram-whack-a-mole-grows-to-19m-blocked-ips-hitting-twitch-spotify-and-more/?guccounter=1|title=Russia\u2019s game of Telegram whack-a-mole grows to 19M blocked IPs, hitting Twitch, Spotify and more \u2013 TechCrunch|website=techcrunch.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref> They include many used by [[Amazon Web Services]] and [[Google Cloud Platform]], due to Telegram's use of the providers to route messages. However, this led to unintended collateral damage due to usage of the platforms by other services in the country, including retail, [[Mastercard]] SecureCode, and [[Mail.ru]]'s Tamtam messaging service. Users ended up needing to use VPN to access the service as a result of the [[internet censorship]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/17/17246150/telegram-russia-ban|title=Russia\u2019s Telegram ban is a big, convoluted mess|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.privateinternetaccess.com/blog/2018/04/russias-telegram-ban-is-a-fiasco-and-its-rendering-millions-of-ip-addresses-inaccessible/|title=Russia\u2019s Telegram Ban Is a Fiasco, and It\u2019s Rendering Millions of IP Addresses Inaccessible|last=Wilmoth|first=Josiah|date=2018-04-17|website=Privacy Online News|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> On 17 April 2018, Russia asked [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]], [[Google Play|Play Store]] and APKMirror to pull Telegram from stores. App Store and Play Store refused the request of Russian government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://9to5mac.com/2018/04/17/russia-apple-ban-telegram-app-store/|title=Russia asks Apple to remove Telegram from App Store after banning the encrypted messaging service|date=2018-04-17|work=9to5Mac|access-date=2018-05-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.howtochatonline.net/news/russian-government-told-apkmirror-to-remove-telegram/|title=Russian Government Told APKMirror to Remove Telegram|last=McInnes|first=Laura|date=April 17, 2018|website=www.howtochatonline.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2018, Roskomnadzor reportedly<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://rkn.gov.ru/news/rsoc/news58106.htm|title=Roskomnadzor requires Apple to stop distributing the Telegram application in Russia and sending its push notifications|date=28 March 2018|access-date=}}</ref> sent a legally binding letter to Apple asking it to remove the app from its Russian App Store and block it from sending push notifications to local users who have already downloaded the app.\n\nOn December 27, 2018 the biggest Russian web search site [[Yandex Search|Yandex.ru]] removed telegram.org from their search results.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lenta.ru/news/2018/12/26/yandex/ |title=\"\u042f\u043d\u0434\u0435\u043a\u0441\" \u0443\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043b \u0438\u0437 \u043f\u043e\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 Telegram |date=27 December 2018 |website=lenta.ru |language=ru}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, the Government of Russia [https://t.me/stopcoronavirusrussia started using] the blocked Telegram platform to spread information related to [[Coronavirus_disease_2019|COVID-19 outbreak.]]\n\n==== India ====\n\n\nIn 2019, it was reported that some ISPs in [[India]] were blocking Telegram traffic, including its official website. <ref>{{cite web |title=Reddit, Telegram among websites blocked in India: internet groups |url=https://in.reuters.com/article/us-india-internet/reddit-telegram-among-websites-blocked-in-india-internet-groups-idINKCN1RF14D |website=Reuters India |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> \n[[Internet Freedom Foundation]], an Indian digital liberties organisation filed an RTI on whether Department of Telecommunications(DoT) had banned Telegram or requested ISPs to block traffic. The response from DoT said that it had no information on why the ISPs were blocking Telegram. <ref>{{cite web |title=Not just porn, users reveal Airtel, Jio, others also banning Telegram, VPNs and proxy sites in India |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/technology/news/story/not-just-porn-users-reveal-airtel-jio-others-also-banning-telegram-vpns-and-proxy-sites-in-india-1454105-2019-02-12 |website=India Today |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> \nThere is little transparency from the DoT and the ISPs in India around content blocking on the Internet, with the DoT using opaque laws to order content removal and the ISPs randomly removing content and  blocking websites without the backing of any legal orders.<ref>{{cite web |title=How India Censors The Web |url=https://cis-india.org/internet-governance/blog/how-india-censors-the-web |website=The Centre for Internet and Society |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Use by terrorists ===\nIn September 2015, in response to a question about the use of Telegram by [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIS), Pavel Durov stated: \"I think that privacy, ultimately, and our right for privacy is more important than our fear of bad things happening, like [[terrorism]].\"<ref>{{cite web|title = Telegram Now Seeing 12BN Daily Messages, Up From 1BN In February|url = https://techcrunch.com/2015/09/21/telegram-now-seeing-12bn-daily-messages-up-from-1m-in-february/|website = TechCrunch|accessdate = 19 November 2015|first = Natasha|last = Lomas}}</ref> Durov sarcastically suggested to ban words because terrorists use them for communication.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vesti.ru/doc.html?id=2687387|title=\u0414\u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u043e \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u043d\u0430 Telegram: \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043b\u0430\u0433\u0430\u044e \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u0441 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0449\u044c\u044e \u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043e\u0431\u0449\u0430\u044e\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b|website=vesti.ru|language=ru}}</ref> ISIS recommended Telegram to its supporters and members<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/01/europe/france-church-attack-telegram/index.html|title=Killers of French priest met 4 days before attack|first1=Margot |last1=Haddad |first2=Tim |last2=Hume|publisher=cnn.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tjournal.ru/p/telegram-jihadi |title=\u041f\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0414\u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u0434\u043b\u044f CNN \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044e \u0441 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0430 \u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0437 Telegram |website =TJournal.ru |first=Gennady |last=Zavolokyn |language=ru |accessdate =20 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csoonline.com/article/3004648/security-awareness/after-paris-isis-moves-propaganda-machine-to-darknet.html|title=After Paris, ISIS moves propaganda machine to Darknet|author=Steve Ragan|date=16 November 2015|work=CSO Online}}</ref> and in October 2015 they were able to double the number of followers of their official channel to 9,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/isis-telegram-channel-doubles-followers-172356843.html|title=Isis Telegram channel doubles followers to 9,000 in less than 1 week|date=12 October 2015|work=Yahoo News}}</ref> In November 2015, Telegram announced that it had blocked 78 public channels operated by ISIS for spreading propaganda and mass communication.<ref>{{cite web|title = Encrypted messaging app Telegram shuts down Islamic State propaganda channels|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/12004892/Encrypted-messaging-app-Telegram-shuts-down-Islamic-State-propaganda-channels.html|website = Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate = 19 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = One app maker has shut down almost 80 secret channels used by ISIS to communicate|url = http://www.businessinsider.com/telegram-blocks-isis-channels-2015-11|website = Business Insider|accessdate = 19 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/telegram-knew-isis-communicate-paris-pavel-durov-a6742126.html|title=Telegram founder knew Isis used the app to communicate before Paris attacks|date=2015-11-20|work=The Independent|access-date=2017-04-24|language=en-GB}}</ref> Telegram stated that it would block public channels and bots that are related to terrorism, but it would not honor \"politically-motivated censorship\" based on \"local restrictions on freedom of speech\" and that it allowed \"peaceful expression of alternative opinions.\"<ref>{{cite web|title = Secretive messaging app used by IS takes down posts|url = https://www.cnbc.com/2015/11/19/telegram-the-messaging-app-used-by-isis-takes-down-78-posts.html|website = CNBC|accessdate = 19 November 2015}}</ref> Telegram's usage for ISIS propaganda reignited the encryption debate and encrypted messaging applications faced new scrutiny.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Encrypted Messaging Apps Face New Scrutiny Over Possible Role in Paris Attacks|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/17/world/europe/encrypted-messaging-apps-face-new-scrutiny-over-possible-role-in-paris-attacks.html|newspaper = [[The New York Times]]|date = 16 November 2015|access-date = 19 November 2015|first = David|last = Sanger|first2 = Nicole|last2 = Perlroth}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Foges|first1=Clare|title=Why is Silicon Valley helping the tech-savvy jihadists? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/12008689/Why-is-Silicon-Valley-helping-the-tech-savvy-jihadists.html|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=9 December 2015}}</ref> It also led to [[Tabloid journalism|tabloids]] labeling Telegram as a \"[[jihadism|jihadi]] messaging app\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Campbell |first=Scott |date=26 July 2016 |title=ISIS warn London 'next to be attacked' as UK churches put on terror alert after French priest murder |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/isis-warn-london-next-attacked-8500399 |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]] |quote=Images threatening attacks in London and other major world capitals have been posted on jihadi messaging app Telegram |access-date=15 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, [[France|French]] anti-terrorism investigators asserted that the two ISIS-directed terrorists who [[2016 Normandy church attack|fatally cut the throat of a priest]] in [[Saint-\u00c9tienne-du-Rouvray]] in [[Normandy]], France, and videoed the murder, had communicated via Telegram and \"used the app to coordinate their plans for the attack\". ISIS's media wing subsequently posted a video on Telegram, showing the pair pledging allegiance. A [[CNN]] news report stated that Telegram had \"become known as a preferred means of communication for the terror group ISIS and was used by the ISIS cell that plotted the [[November 2015 Paris attacks|Paris terror attacks in November]]\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn June 2017, the Russian communications regulator [[Roscomnadzor]] hinted at the possibility of [[blocking Telegram in Russia]] due to its usage by terrorists.<ref>(in Russian) {{cite web|last1=Martynov|first1=Kirill |title=\u0417\u0430\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0422\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c|url=https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2017/06/24/72903-zanyat-telegram|website=Novaya Gazeta|accessdate=26 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Director General of Application and Informatics of the Indonesian [[Ministry of Communication and Informatics (Indonesia)|Ministry of Communication and Informatics]], Semuel Abrijani Pangerapan, said eleven Telegram DNS servers were blocked because many channels in the service \"promoted radicalism, terrorism, hatred, bomb assembly, civil attack, disturbing images, and other propaganda contrary to Indonesian laws and regulations.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Widiartanto|first1=Yoga Hastyadi |title=Ini Alasan Pemerintah Blokir Telegram|trans-title=This is the Reason Why the Government Blocks Telegram|url=http://tekno.kompas.com/read/2017/07/14/20495927/ini-alasan-resmi-pemerintah-blokir-telegram|accessdate=15 July 2017|work=[[Kompas]]|date=14 July 2017|language=id}}</ref> In August 2017, Indonesia lifted the block after countermeasures against negative content were deployed in association with Telegram LLP.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indonesian government lifts ban on messaging service Telegram|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/indonesian-government-lifts-ban-on-messaging-service-telegram|website=The Straits Times|publisher=SPH Digital News|date=11 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Telegram participated in [[Europol]]'s Internet Referral Action Day.<ref name=\"europol.europa.eu\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.europol.europa.eu/newsroom/news/europol-and-telegram-take-terrorist-propaganda-online|title=Europol and Telegram take on terrorist propaganda online|website=Europol|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> As a result, Telegram expanded and strengthened its terrorist content detection and removal efforts. Over 43,000 terrorist-related bots and channels were removed from Telegram. According to U.S. officials, the crackdown on Telegram was especially effective and seems to be having lasting impact.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/europe/struggles-regain-social-media-footing-after-europe-crackdown|title=IS Struggles to Regain Social Media Footing After Europe Crackdown|website=Voice of America|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> According to Europol, Telegram has put forth considerable effort in removing abusers of its platform.<ref name=\"europol.europa.eu\"/>\n\n===White supremacists===\nAn article published by ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'' magazine on January 19, 2020, says that the [[Anti-Defamation League]] has called Telegram a white supremacist \"safe haven\" and a valuable tool for right-wing extremists. The article said Neo-nazi and fascist hate groups were using the Telegram app to organize [[2020 VCDL Lobby day|a gun rally]] in Richmond, Virginia, on January 20, 2020.<ref>[https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2020/01/telegram-nazis-richmond/?fbclid=IwAR2xH1yfeZ1LQAh2CnExQ35rHQptBf5AgCofPBpRQsydYexSwNfi6_3NMgs Ahead of Richmond Rally, Apple and Google Are Letting Nazis Use This App to Coordinate] By Ali Breland, Mother Jones, 19 Jan 2020</ref> The neo-Nazi white separatist paramilitary hate group [[The Base (hate group)|''The Base'']] switched over to Telegram after being blocked on most social media platforms, including Twitter, YouTube, and Gab, a favorite among extremists. After a number of arrests of ''The Base'' members in January 2020, a note appeared on its official Telegram account warning people to stop posting.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/22/us/white-supremacy-the-base.html</ref> In August 2019 white supremacist [[Christopher Cantwell]] posted [[Antisemitism|anti-Semitic]] comments on Telegram.<ref>https://slate.com/technology/2019/08/telegram-white-nationalists-el-paso-shooting-facebook.html</ref>\n\nThe Anti-Defamation League notes that Telegram was founded by the same two Russian brothers who founded [[VK (service)|VKontakte (VK)]], which is known for its lack of moderation when it comes to white supremism. While Telegram's terms of service prohibit the promotion of violence, they have allowed violent videos posted by mass shooters Brenton Tarrant ([[Christchurch mosque shootings|Christchurch, New Zealand]]) and Stephan Balliet ([[Halle synagogue shooting|Halle, Germany]]), although other social media platforms had removed them. The League also points to the RapeWaffen Division channel, which openly advocates rape and murder as part of a race war.<ref>{{cite web|website=ADL.org|title=Telegram: The Latest Safe Haven for White Supremacists|date=December 2, 2019|accessdate=March 11, 2020|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/telegram-the-latest-safe-haven-for-white-supremacists}}</ref>\n\n=== Illegal uses ===\nTelegram allows users to report abusive public domain posts and deletes terrorist groups' public chats and child pornography. But Telegram does not share or redress any abusing report. Telegram is still being actively used for illegal purposes. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/telegram-app-a-safe-haven-for-cyber-criminals-kerala-police-to-hc/1775014/|title=Telegram app a safe haven for cyber criminals: Kerala police to HC|work=Financial Express}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-indonesia-security-apps-idUSKBN1AH40K|title=Indonesia to lift ban on Telegram message service over security|date=2017-08-01|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-12-01|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-there-39s-illegal-content-on-telegram-how-do-i-take-it-down|title=Telegram F.A.Q.|website=Telegram|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://t.me/isiswatch/2|title=ISIS Watch|website=Telegram|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref>\n\n== Telegram Open Network ICO ==\nIn December 2017, cryptocurrency blog Cointelegraph reported that Telegram was planning to launch a [[blockchain]] platform and native [[cryptocurrency]]. In January 2018, [[TechCrunch]] confirmed the news, referring to multiple sources.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/01/08/telegram-open-network/|title=Telegram plans multi-billion dollar ICO for chat&nbsp;cryptocurrency|last=Butcher|first=Mike|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2018-01-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe company put together an [[Initial coin offering|Initial Coin Offering]] (ICO)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/hardfork/2018/01/09/telegram-ico-white-paper-leak|title=Here is the leaked white paper for the massive Telegram ICO|last=Mix|work=HardFork|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref> to fund development of a new blockchain platform, to be called the \"Telegram Open Network\" (TON). The offering was organised as a SAFT (Simple Agreement for Future Tokens), selling futures on tokens to be called GRAM.<ref name=\":2\" /> A 23-page white paper<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1ucUeKg_NiR8RxNAonb8Q55jZha03WC0O/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=TON.pdf|website=Google Docs}}</ref> and a detailed 132-page technical paper<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1lqVlrgiztnA5dkOHP7-ENDKT1FgZuCUV/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=TON Technology.pdf|website=Google Docs}}</ref> for the plan were released.\n\nThe offering ran in two rounds, each taking in $850 million. Russian tech news site  calculated the first round as offering 2.25 billion tokens at $0.38 each, with a minimum purchase of $20 million, and the second as offering 640 million tokens at $1.33 each, with a minimum purchase of $1 million.<ref name=\"cnews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnews.ru/news/top/2018-04-02_pri_kakih_usloviyah_telegram_vernet_investoram|title=Under what conditions will Telegram return to investors the collected $ 2.55 billion|last1=Korolev|first1=Igor|date=2 Apr 2018|website=CNews|language=Russian|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/internet/telegram-messenger-service-raises-1-7-billion-from-cryptocoin/article/518798|title=Telegram messenger service raises $1.7 billion from cryptocoin|last1=Hanly|first1=Ken|date=1 Apr 2018|website=Digital Journal|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"verge\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/1/17186004/telegram-presale-open-network-app-ico-cryptocurrency-ton|title=Telegram has raised a total of $1.7 billion from its two pre-ICO sales|last1=Liptak|first1=Andrew|date=1 Apr 2018|website=The Verge|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2018, the firm had reported raising $1.7 billion through the ongoing ICO.<ref name=\"shen1\">{{cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2018/03/30/bitcoin-price-telegram-ico-presale/|title=Even as Bitcoin Languishes, Telegram Raises $1.7 Billion Ahead of Largest ICO Ever|last1=Shen|first1=Lucinda|date=March 31, 2018|accessdate=March 31, 2018|publisher=Fortune}}</ref> Company officials have not made any public statements regarding the ICO. As of spring 2018, the only official sources of information were the two [[Form D|Forms D]] that Telegram filed with the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2018/04/131248-telegram-files-new-form-d-with-sec-indicating-1-7-billion-will-be-raised/|title=Telegram Files New Form D with SEC Indicating $1.7 Billion will be Raised {{!}} Crowdfund Insider|date=2018-04-02|work=Crowdfund Insider|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOnly the pre-ICO rounds were conducted; the public ICO was cancelled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/telegram-messaging-app-scraps-plans-for-public-coin-offering-1525281933?ns=prod/accounts-wsj|title=Telegram Messaging App Scraps Plans for Public Coin Offering|last=Vigna|first=Paul|date=2018-05-02|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-11-11|language=en-US}}</ref> The network has yet to be released.\n\nOn 11 October 2019, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission filed an emergency action and obtained a temporary restraining order against Telegram over an alleged unregistered and ongoing digital token offering in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sec.gov/news/press-release/2019-212|title=SEC Halts Alleged $1.7 Billion Unregistered Digital Token Offering {{!}} U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|date=2019-10-11|work=U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|access-date=2019-10-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Breach ==\nAn Elasticsearch database holding 42 million records 42 million user IDs and phone numbers were exposed online without a password. The accounts belong to users in Iran, which were extracted from an unofficial government sanctioned version of telegram; was found on March 30, 2020. It took 11 days for the database to be taken down, but the researchers say the data was accessed by other parties, including a hacker who reported the information to a specialized forum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comparitech.com/blog/information-security/iranian-telegram-accounts-leaked/|title=Report: 42M Iranian \"Telegram\" User IDs & Phone Numbers Leaked Online|date=2020-03-30|website=Comparitech|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://securityboulevard.com/2020/04/elasticsearch-database-with-42-million-records-of-iranian-citizen-found-exposed-online/|title=Elasticsearch Database with 42 Million Records of Iranian Citizen Found Exposed Online|last=April 7|first=Silviu STAHIE on|last2=2020|date=2020-04-07|website=Security Boulevard|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hotforsecurity.bitdefender.com/blog/elasticsearch-database-with-42-million-records-of-iranian-citizen-found-exposed-online-22852.html|title=Elasticsearch Database with 42 Million Records of Iranian Citizen...|last=STAHIE|first=Silviu|date=2020-04-07|website=HOTforSecurity|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Telecommunications|Free and open-source software|Freedom of speech}}\n* [[Comparison of instant messaging clients]]\n* [[Internet privacy]]\n* [[Secure instant messaging]]\n* [[Signal (software)]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://eprint.iacr.org/2015/1177.pdf|title=On the CCA (in)security of MTProto|last1=Jakobsen|first1=Jakob|last2=Orlandi|first2=Claudio|date=8 December 2015|website=Cryptology ePrint Archive|publisher=International Association for Cryptologic Research (IACR)|format=PDF|accessdate=11 December 2015|ref={{harvid|Jakobsen|Orlandi|2015}}}}\n* {{Cite conference|last1=Rottermanner|first1=Christoph|last2=Kieseberg|first2=Peter|last3=Huber|first3=Markus|last4=Schmiedecker|first4=Martin|last5=Schrittwieser|first5=Sebastian|date=December 2015|title=Privacy and Data Protection in Smartphone Messengers|url=https://www.sba-research.org/wp-content/uploads/publications/paper_drafthp.pdf|format=PDF|conference=Proceedings of the 17th International Conference on Information Integration and Web-based Applications & Services (iiWAS2015)|publisher=ACM International Conference Proceedings Series|volume=|isbn=978-1-4503-3491-4|accessdate=18 March 2016|ref={{harvid|Rottermanner|Kieseberg|Huber|Schmiedecker|2015}}}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Telegram Messenger}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Instant messaging}}\n\n[[Category:2013 software]]\n[[Category:Communication software]]\n[[Category:Cross-platform software]]\n[[Category:Free and open-source Android software]]\n[[Category:Instant messaging clients]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n[[Category:Linux software]]\n[[Category:Software that uses Qt]]\n[[Category:Windows Phone software]]\n[[Category:Telegram (software)| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Telegram (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Free cross-platform messenging service}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Telegram<!--Technical ID; must not be changed. Use \"title\" to change what is displayed instead.-->\n| title = Telegram Messenger\n| logo = Telegram 2019 Logo.svg\n| screenshot = Telegram Chats List on iOS.png\n| screenshot size = 220px\n| caption = Telegram running on an [[iPhone]]\n| developer = Telegram FZ LLC<br>Telegram Messenger Inc.\n| released = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2013|8|14|}}\n| ver layout = stacked\n| programming language = [[C++]]\n| platform = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Windows Phone]], [[Windows NT]], [[macOS]], [[GNU/Linux]], [[Web app|Web platform]]\n| language count = 14\n| language footnote = <ref>{{cite web|title=Live Locations, Media Player and Languages|url=https://telegram.org/blog/live-locations|website=telegram.org|publisher=Telegram Messenger LLP|accessdate= 12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Translating Telegram|url=https://translations.telegram.org/|website=translations.telegram.org|publisher=Telegram Messenger LLP|accessdate= 12 April 2018}}</ref>\n| language = [[English language|English]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[German language|German]], [[Dutch language|Dutch]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Arabic]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[French language|French]], [[Languages of Indonesia|Indonesian]], [[Malay language|Malay]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n| genre = [[Instant messaging]]\n| license = [[GNU General Public License|GNU GPLv2 or GPLv3]] (clients),<ref name=\"teleapps\" /> proprietary (server)\n| alexa = {{DecreasePositive}} 188 ({{asof|2020|04|13|alt=April 2020}})<ref>{{cite web |title=telegram.org Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic - Alexa |url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/telegram.org |website=alexa.com |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|https://telegram.org}}\n}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name             = Telegram Messenger LLP\n| logo             = [[File:Telegram 2019 Logo.svg|100px]]\n| collapsible      = \n| screenshot       = \n| caption          = \n| dissolved        =\n| location         = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]<br>(legal domicile)<br>[[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]]<br>(operational center)\n| locations        = \n| founder          = {{Unbulleted list|[[Nikolai Durov]]|[[Pavel Durov]]}}\n| chairman         = \n| chairperson      = \n| president        = \n| CEO              = Pavel Durov\n| MD               =\n| GM               = \n| industry         = [[Software]]\n| products         = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            =\n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| url              = {{URL|https://telegram.org/}}\n| advertising      = \n| language         =\n| footnotes        = \n| logo_size        = \n| company_type     = \n| traded_as        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|2013|3}}\n| incorporated     =\n| area_served      = Global\n| key_people       = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| num_employees    = 351 (2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://craft.co/telegram-messenger|title=Telegram Company profile|date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n| subsid           = \n| programming_language = \n| website_type     =\n| num_users        =\n| launch_date      = \n| current_status   = \n| collapsetext     = \n}}\n'''Telegram''' is a [[Cloud computing|cloud]]-based [[instant messaging]] and [[voice over IP]] service. Telegram [[client (computing)|client]] apps are available for [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Windows Phone]], [[Windows NT]], [[macOS]] and [[GNU/Linux]].<ref name=\"teleapps\">{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/apps|title=List of Telegram applications|date=6 February 2014}}</ref> Users can send messages and exchange photos, videos, [[Sticker (messaging)|sticker]]s, audio and files of any type.\n\nTelegram's client-side code is [[open-source software]] but the source code for recent versions is not always immediately published,<ref name=\"GitHub\">{{cite web|url=https://github.com/DrKLO/Telegram/commits/master|title=Latest commits from official repository (Android version)|date=10 April 2016|website=Github|access-date=}}</ref> whereas its server-side code is closed-source and proprietary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-why-not-open-source-everything|title=Telegram F.A.Q.|website=Telegram|access-date=2017-10-01}}</ref> The service also provides [[Application programming interface|APIs]] to independent developers. In March 2018, Telegram stated that it had 200 million [[monthly active users]].<ref name=\"TelegramUsersMarch2018\">{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/200-million|title=200,000,000 Monthly Active Users|date=22 March 2018|website=Telegram}}</ref>\n\nDefault messages and media in Telegram are encrypted when stored on its servers, but can be accessed by the Telegram service provider, who holds the [[encryption key]]s. In addition Telegram provides optional [[End-to-end encryption|end-to-end encrypted]] \"secret\" chats between two online users, yet not for groups or channels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-why-not-just-make-all-chats-secret|title=Telegram F.A.Q.|website=Telegram|access-date=2017-10-01}}</ref>\n\nThe client-server communication is also encrypted.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://telegra.ph/Why-you-should-stop-reading-Gizmodo-right-now-Long|title=Why you should stop reading Gizmodo right now|date=2017-06-21|work=Telegraph|access-date=2017-10-01}}</ref> The service provides end-to-end encryption for voice calls.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://core.telegram.org/techfaq#q-how-are-voice-calls-authenticated|title=FAQ for the Technically Inclined|website=core.telegram.org|access-date=2017-10-01}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Development ===\nTelegram was launched in 2013 by the brothers [[Nikolai Durov|Nikolai]] and [[Pavel Durov]]. Previously, the pair founded the [[Russia]]n social network [[VK (social network)|VK]], which they left when it was taken over by the [[Mail.ru Group]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"TechCrunch\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/10/27/meet-telegram-a-secure-messaging-app-from-the-founders-of-vk-russias-largest-social-network/|title=Meet Telegram, A Secure Messaging App From The Founders Of VK, Russia\u2019s Largest Social Network|last=Shu|first=Catherine|date=27 October 2013|website=TechCrunch|access-date=18 March 2016}}</ref> Nikolai Durov created the [[MTProto]] protocol that is the basis for the messenger, while Pavel provided financial support and infrastructure through his [[Axel Neff#Digital Fortress LLC|Digital Fortress]] fund with partner [[Axel Neff]] joining as a second co-founder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/08/30/idUS74722569420130830|title=Russia's Zuckerberg launches Telegram, a new instant messenger service|date=30 August 2013|website=Reuters|access-date=18 March 2016}}</ref> Telegram Messenger LLP states that its end goal is not to bring profit,<ref>[https://telegram.org/faq#q-how-are-you-going-to-make-money-out-of-this Telegram F.A.Q], \"...making profits will never be an end-goal for Telegram.\"</ref><ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2014/2/25/5445864/telegram-messenger-hottest-app-in-the-world Why Telegram has become the hottest messaging app in the world], The Verge. Retrieved 25 February 2014. \"Telegram operates as a non-profit organization, and doesn\u2019t plan to charge for its services.\"</ref> but it is not currently structured as a non-profit organization.<ref name=\"WaPo1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-intersect/wp/2015/11/23/the-secret-american-origins-of-telegram-the-encrypted-messaging-app-favored-by-the-islamic-state/|title=The secret American origins of Telegram, the encrypted messaging app favored by the Islamic State|last1=Dewey|first1=Caitlin|date=November 23, 2015|accessdate=31 March 2018|publisher=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nTelegram is registered as both an English [[Limited liability partnership|LLP]]<ref>{{cite web|title = Telegram - Android Apps on Google Play|url = https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=org.telegram.messenger|website = play.google.com|accessdate = 19 November 2015}}</ref> and an American [[Limited liability company|LLC]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Telegram Messenger on the App Store|url = https://itunes.apple.com/app/telegram-messenger/id686449807|website = App Store|accessdate = 19 November 2015}}</ref> It does not disclose where it rents offices or which legal entities it uses to rent them, citing the need to \"shelter the team from unnecessary influence\" and protect users from governmental data requests.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Lunch with the FT: Pavel Durov|url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/21c5c7f2-20b1-11e5-ab0f-6bb9974f25d0.html|newspaper = [[Financial Times]]|access-date = 19 November 2015|first = John|last = Thornhill|date = 3 July 2015}}</ref> Pavel Durov has said that the service was headquartered in [[Berlin]], [[Germany]], between 2014<ref name=\"TheVergeKorea\">{{cite web|url = https://www.theverge.com/2014/10/6/6926205/surveillance-drives-south-koreans-to-encrypted-messaging-apps|title = Surveillance drives South Koreans to encrypted messaging apps|date = 6 October 2014|website = [[The Verge]]|accessdate = 19 November 2015|first = Russell|last = Brandom}}</ref> and early 2015, but moved to different jurisdictions after failing to obtain residence permits for everyone on the team.<ref name=\"Turton-2017-09-29\">{{cite web|last1=Turton|first1=William|title=What isn\u2019t Telegram saying about its connections to the Kremlin?|url=https://theoutline.com/post/2348/what-isn-t-telegram-saying-about-its-connections-to-the-kremlin|website=The Outline|accessdate=11 October 2017|date=29 September 2017}}</ref> Durov left Russia and is said to be moving from country to country with a small group of computer programmers consisting of 15 core members.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|title = Once Celebrated in Russia, the Programmer Pavel Durov Chooses Exile|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/03/technology/once-celebrated-in-russia-programmer-pavel-durov-chooses-exile.html|newspaper = [[The New York Times]]|date = 2 December 2014|access-date = 19 November 2015|first = Danny|last = Hakim}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-telecoms-mobileworld-telegram-idUSKCN0VW2CM|title=Telegram app free-speech advocate no stranger to Apple-FBI woes|date=23 February 2016|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref> According to press reports, Telegram had employees in [[St. Petersburg]].<ref name=\"Turton-2017-09-29\"/> The Telegram team is currently based in Dubai.<ref name=\"Bloomberg-2017-12-12\">{{cite news|title = This $5 Billion Encrypted App Isn't for Sale at Any Price | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-12/cryptic-russian-crusader-says-his-5-billion-app-can-t-be-bought|newspaper = [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] | date = 12 December 2017 |access-date = 22 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Usage numbers ===\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=400\n|height=160\n|type=line\n|xType=date\n|xAxisFormat=%b %Y\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|yGrid= \n|x=2013-08-14, 2013-10-27, 2014-01-26, 2014-03-24, 2014-12-08, 2015-09-21, 2016-02-23, 2017-12-12, 2018-03-22, 2020-04-18\n|y1=0, 0.2, 2, 35, 50, 60, 100, 180, 200, 400\n|xAxisTitle=Telegram timeline (August 2013 \u2013 April 2020)\n|yAxisTitle=Monthly active users (mil.)\n}}\nIn October 2013, Telegram had 100,000 daily active users.<ref name=\"TechCrunch\" /> On 24 March 2014, Telegram announced that it had reached 35 million monthly users and 15 million daily active users.<ref>{{Citation|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/03/24/telegram-hits-35m-monthly-users-15m-daily-with-8b-messages-received-over-30-days/|publisher=TechCrunch|title=Telegram Hits 35M Monthly Users, 15M Daily With 8B Messages Received Over 30 Days|date=24 March 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, South Korean governmental surveillance plans drove many of its citizens to switch to Telegram.<ref name=\"TheVergeKorea\" /> In December 2014, Telegram announced that it had 50 million active users, generating 1 billion daily messages, and that it had 1 million new users signing up on its service every week<ref>{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/billion|publisher=Telegram|title=Telegram Reaches 1 Billion Daily Messages|date=8 December 2014}}</ref>, traffic doubled in five months with 2 billion daily messages.<ref>{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/2-billion|publisher=Telegram|title=Telegram Hits 2 Billion Messages Sent Daily|date=13 May 2015}}</ref> In September 2015, an announcement stated that the app had 60 million active users and delivered 12 billion daily messages.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://techcrunch.com/2015/09/21/telegram-now-seeing-12bn-daily-messages-up-from-1m-in-february/|title = Telegram Now Seeing 12BN Daily Messages, up From 1BN in February|date = 21 September 2015|accessdate = 19 November 2015|website = [[Techcrunch]]|last = Lomas|first = Natasha}}</ref> In February 2016, Telegram announced that it had 100 million monthly active users, with 350,000 new users signing up every day, delivering 15 billion messages daily.<ref>{{cite web|title = Encrypted Messaging App Telegram Hits 100M Monthly Active Users, 350k New Users Each Day|url = https://techcrunch.com/2016/02/23/encrypted-messaging-app-telegram-hits-100m-monthly-active-users-350k-new-users-each-day/|website = TechCrunch|access-date = 23 February 2016|first = Matt|last = Burns|date = 23 February 2016}}</ref> In December 2017, Telegram reached 180 million monthly active users.<ref name=\"Bloomberg-2017-12-12\" /> In March 2018, Telegram reached 200 million monthly active users.<ref name=\"TelegramUsersMarch2018\"/> On March 14, 2019, Pavel Durov claimed that \u201c3 million new users signed up for Telegram within the last 24 hours.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lomas |first1=Natasha |title=Telegram gets 3M new signups during Facebook apps\u2019 outage |url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/03/14/telegram-gets-3m-new-signups-during-facebook-apps-outage/ |website=TechCrunch |accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref> Durov didn't specify what prompted this flood of new sign-ups, but the period matched a prolonged technical outage experienced by Facebook and its family of apps, including Instagram.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shieber |first1=Jonathan |title=Update: Facebook, Instagram and Messenger were down for many users |url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/03/13/facebook-instagram-and-messenger-are-down-for-some-users/ |website=TechCrunch |accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the number of monthly Telegram users as of October 2019 is 300 million people worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/complaints/2019/comp-pr2019-212.pdf|title=SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION,        ::Plaintiff,  :19 Civ. 9439(PKC):-against -:ECF Case:TELEGRAM GROUPINC.andTON ISSUERINC.,|last=|first=|date=October 11, 2019|website=The US Securities and Exchange Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Features ==\n\n=== Account ===\n[[File:Telegram account self-destruction.png|thumb|Account self-destruction]]\n[[File:Telegram account is limited.png|thumb|The user was [[Block (Internet)|limited]].]]\nTelegram accounts are tied to telephone numbers and are verified by [[Short Message Service|SMS]].<ref name=\"Lopez\">{{Citation|url=http://www.applesfera.com/aplicaciones-ios-1/configurando-telegram-en-el-iphone-en-la-web-y-en-el-mac|title=Configurando Telegram en el iPhone, en la web y en el Mac|first=Miguel|last=Lopez|trans-title=Configuring Telegram in the Apple iPhone, the Web and the Mac|language=es|publisher=Applesfera|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> Users can add multiple devices to their account and receive messages on each one. Connected devices can be removed individually or all at once. The associated number can be changed at any time and when doing so, the user's contacts will receive the new number automatically.<ref name=\"Lopez\" /><ref name=\"way-transf\">{{cite web|url = http://www.wayerless.com/2014/12/telegram-se-actualiza-permitiendo-ahora-migrar-tus-conversaciones-y-contactos-a-una-linea-nueva/|first = Jonathan|last = Munizaga|date = 1 December 2014|trans-title = Telegram already allows migrating conversations and contacts to a new line|title = Telegram ya permite migrar conversaciones y contactos a una l\u00ednea nueva|publisher = Wayerless|accessdate = 2 December 2014|language = es|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141219220850/http://www.wayerless.com/2014/12/telegram-se-actualiza-permitiendo-ahora-migrar-tus-conversaciones-y-contactos-a-una-linea-nueva/|archivedate = 19 December 2014|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"te-transf\">{{cite web|language = es|url = http://www.tuexpertoapps.com/2014/12/02/telegram-ahora-permite-traspasar-mensajes-al-cambiar-de-numero/|first = David G|last = Mateo|date = 1 December 2014|title = Telegram ahora permite traspasar mensajes al cambiar de n\u00famero|publisher = TuExperto|accessdate = 2 December 2014}}</ref> In addition, a user can set up an [[Pseudonym|alias]] that allows them to send and receive messages without exposing their phone number.<ref name=\"cs2.0\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/10/23/secure-messaging-app-telegram-adds-usernames-and-snapchat-like-hold-to-view-for-media/|title=Secure Messaging App Telegram Adds Usernames And Snapchat-Like Hold-To-View For Media|publisher=Techcrunch|date=23 October 2014|accessdate=23 October 2014}}</ref> Telegram accounts can be deleted at any time and they are deleted automatically after six months of inactivity by default, which can optionally be changed to 1 month and 12 months. Users can replace exact \"last seen\" timestamps with broader messages such as \"last seen recently\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Hiding Last Seen Time - Done Right|url=https://telegram.org/blog/privacy-revolution|accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe default method of [[authentication]] that Telegram uses for [[login]]s is SMS-based single-factor authentication.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kirk|first1=Jeremy|title=How much trust can you put in Telegram messenger?|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2871412/how-much-trust-can-you-put-in-telegram-messenger.html|website=PC World|publisher=IDG|accessdate=4 May 2016|date=15 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Rad-2015-01-09\"/> All that is needed in order to log into an account and gain access to that user's cloud-based messages is a one-time passcode that is sent via SMS to the user's phone number.<ref name=\"Rad-2015-01-09\">{{cite web|last1=Rad|first1=Alex|title=A 264 Attack On Telegram, And Why A Super Villain Doesn't Need It To Read Your Telegram Chats.|url=http://www.alexrad.me/discourse/a-264-attack-on-telegram-and-why-a-super-villain-doesnt-need-it-to-read-your-telegram-chats.html|website=alexrad.me|type=Blog|accessdate=4 May 2016|date=9 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425091011/http://www.alexrad.me/discourse/a-264-attack-on-telegram-and-why-a-super-villain-doesnt-need-it-to-read-your-telegram-chats.html|archivedate=25 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Lokot-2016-05-02\"/> These login SMS messages are known to have been intercepted in Iran, Russia and Germany, possibly in coordination with phone companies.<ref name=\"Lokot-2016-05-02\"/><ref name=\"Menn-2016-08-02\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lipp|first1=Sebastian|last2=Hoppenstedt|first2=Max|title=Exklusiv: Wie das BKA Telegram-Accounts von Terrorverd\u00e4chtigen knackt|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/de/read/exklusiv-wie-das-bka-telegram-accounts-von-terrorverdaechtigen-knackt|website=Motherboard|publisher=Vice Media Inc.|accessdate=28 August 2016|language=German|date=26 August 2016}}</ref> Pavel Durov has said that Telegram users in \"troubled countries\" should enable [[two-factor authentication]] by creating passwords, which Telegram allows, but does not require.<ref name=\"Lokot-2016-05-02\">{{cite web|last1=Lokot|first1=Tetyana|title=Is Telegram Really Safe for Activists Under Threat? These Two Russians Aren't So Sure.|url=https://advox.globalvoices.org/2016/05/02/is-telegram-really-safe-for-activists-under-threat-these-two-russians-arent-so-sure/|website=Advox|publisher=Global Voices|accessdate=4 May 2016|date=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Menn-2016-08-02\">{{cite news|last1=Menn|first1=Joseph|last2=Torbati|first2=Yeganeh|title=Exclusive: Hackers accessed Telegram messaging accounts in Iran - researchers|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iran-cyber-telegram-exclusive-idUSKCN10D1AM|accessdate=3 August 2016|work=Reuters|publisher=Thomson Reuters|date=2 August 2016|location=San Francisco/Washington}}</ref>\n\n=== Cloud-based messages ===\nTelegram's default messages are cloud-based and can be accessed on any of the user's connected devices. Users can share photos, videos, audio messages and other files (up to 1.5 [[gigabyte]] in size per file). Users can send messages to other users individually or to groups of up to 200,000 members.<ref name=\"Venture-5k\">{{cite news|url=https://twitter.com/telegram/status/922426780316774401|title=Group chats on Telegram can now have up to 1,00,000 members. Admins can use advanced permissions and butler bots to keep the peace.|date=23 October 2017|via=Twitter.com}}</ref> Sent messages can be edited within 48 hours after they have been sent and deleted at any time on both sides. This gives user an ability to correct typos and retract messages that were sent by mistake.<ref name=\"Telegram Unsend Messages\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/unsend-and-usage|publisher=Telegram|title=Unsend Messages, Network Usage, and More|date=3 January 2017|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> The transmission of messages to Telegram Messenger LLP's servers is encrypted with the service's [[MTProto]] protocol.<ref name=\"how-secure\" /> According to Telegram's privacy policy, \"all data is stored heavily encrypted and the encryption keys in each case are stored in several other DCs in different jurisdictions. This way local engineers or physical intruders cannot get access to user data\".<ref>{{cite web|title = Telegram Privacy Policy|url = https://telegram.org/privacy|website = Telegram|access-date = 17 January 2016}}</ref> This makes the messages' security roughly comparable to that of e-mail. Here, most providers employ client-server encryption as well, however usually with the standardized protocol [[Transport Layer Security]]. E-mails may or may not be encrypted on the servers. Telegram cloud messages and media remain on the servers at least until deleted by all participants.\n\n=== Bots ===\nIn June 2015, Telegram launched a platform for third-party developers to create [[IM bot|bots]].<ref name=\"Telegram Bot Platform\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/bot-revolution|publisher=Telegram|title=Telegram Bot Platform|date=24 June 2015|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref> Bots are Telegram accounts operated by programs. They can respond to messages or [[Mention (blogging)|mentions]], can be invited into groups and can be integrated into other programs. It also accepts online payments with credit cards and [[Apple Pay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/payments|title=Payments for Bots|website=Telegram|access-date=2018-02-12}}</ref> Dutch website ''[[Tweakers]]'' reported that an invited bot can potentially read all group messages when the bot controller changes the access settings silently at a later point in time. Telegram pointed out that it considered implementing a feature that would announce such a status change within the relevant group.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://tweakers.net/nieuws/104386/telegram-bots-kunnen-relatief-ongemerkt-meelezen-in-groepsgesprekken.html|title = Telegram-bots kunnen relatief ongemerkt meelezen in groepsgesprekken|date = 23 July 2015|accessdate = 25 October 2015|website = [[Tweakers]]|last = Schellevis|first = Joost|language = nl}}</ref> Also there are inline bots, which can be used from any chat screen. In order to activate an inline bot, user needs to type in the message field a bot's username and query. The bot then will offer its content. User can choose from that content and send it within a chat.<ref name=\"Inline Bots\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/inline-bots|publisher=Telegram|title=Introducing Inline Bots|date=4 January 2016|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Channels ===\nIn September 2015, Telegram added channels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/channels|title=Channels: Broadcasting Done Right|date=2015-09-22|website=Telegram|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> Channels are a form of one-way messaging where admins are able to post messages but other users are not. Any user is able to create and subscribe to channels. Channels can be created for broadcasting messages to an unlimited number of subscribers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lobao|first1=Martim|title=Telegram v3.2 Brings Channels For Broadcasting Your Messages To The World|url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2015/09/22/telegram-v3-2-brings-channels-broadcasting-messages-world/|work=Android Police|date=22 September 2015}}</ref> Channels can be publicly available with an alias and a permanent URL so anyone can join. Users who join a channel can see the entire message history. Users can join and leave channels at any time. Depending on a channel's settings, messages may be signed with the channel's name or with the username of the admin who posted them. Non-admin users are unable to see other users who've subscribed to the channel. Furthermore, users can mute a channel, meaning that the user will still receive messages, but won't be notified. Admins can give permission to post comments on the Telegram channel with help of bots. The admin of the channel can obtain general data about the channel. Each message has its own view counter, showing how many users have seen this message, this includes views from forwarded messages. As of May 2019, the creator of a channel can add a discussion group, a separate group where messages in the channel are automatically posted for subscribers to communicate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/privacy-discussions-web-bots|title=Focused Privacy, Discussion Groups, Seamless Web Bots and More|date=2019-05-31|website=Telegram|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] moved their messenger-based newsletter service from [[WhatsApp]] to Telegram after the former banned bulk and automated messaging.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-04/how-to-follow-bloomberg-on-telegram|title=How to Follow Bloomberg on Telegram|last=Hess|first=Megan|date=December 3, 2019|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Jan 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://digiday.com/media/bloomberg-news-using-telegram/|title=How Bloomberg News is using Telegram|last=Ting|first=Deanna|date=2020-01-10|website=Digiday|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> The news service is attempting to grow its audience outside the U.S.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n=== Stickers ===\n\nStickers are cloud-based, high-definition images intended to provide more expressive [[emoji]]. When typing in an emoji, the user is offered to send the respective sticker instead. Stickers come in collections called \"sets\", and multiple stickers can be offered for one emoji. Telegram comes with one default sticker set,<ref name=\"Telegram Stickers\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/stickers-meet-art-and-history|publisher=Telegram|title=Telegram Stickers|date=2 January 2015|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> but users can install additional sticker sets provided by third-party contributors. Sticker sets installed from one client become automatically available to all other clients. Sticker images use [[WebP]] file format, which is better optimized to be transmitted over internet.\n\n=== Drafts ===\n\nDrafts are unfinished messages synced across user devices. One can start typing a message on one device and continue on another. The draft will persist in editing area on any device until it is sent or removed.<ref name=\"Drafts\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/drafts|publisher=Telegram|title=Drafts, Picture-in-Picture, and More|date=14 June 2016|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Secret chats ===\n[[File:Telegram secret chat - en.png|thumb|200px|A \"secret chat\" confirmation notice - screenshot from [[Android Marshmallow]].]]\nMessages can also be sent with client-to-client encryption in so-called secret chats. These messages are encrypted with the service's [[MTProto]] protocol.<ref name=\"techfaq\" /> Unlike Telegram's cloud-based messages, messages sent within a secret chat can be accessed only on the device upon which the secret chat was initiated and the device upon which the secret chat was accepted; they cannot be accessed on other devices.<ref name=\"TechCrunch\" /><ref name=\"how-secure\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-how-secure-is-telegram|publisher=Telegram|work=FAQ|title=How secure is Telegram?}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|publisher=Telegram|url=https://core.telegram.org/mtproto|title=Description of MTProto Mobile Protocol}}</ref> Messages sent within secret chats can, in principle, be deleted at any time and can optionally self-destruct.<ref>{{harvnb|Rottermanner|Kieseberg|Huber|Schmiedecker|2015|p=2}}</ref>\n\nSecret chats have to be initiated and accepted by an invitation, upon which the encryption keys for the session are exchanged. Users in a secret chat can verify that no [[man-in-the-middle attack]] has occurred by comparing pictures that visualize their [[public key fingerprint]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hamburger|first1=Ellis|title=Why Telegram has become the hottest messaging app in the world|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/2/25/5445864/telegram-messenger-hottest-app-in-the-world|website=The Verge|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=17 March 2016|date=25 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Telegram, secret chats have supported [[perfect forward secrecy]] since December 2014. Encryption keys are periodically changed after a key has been used more than 100 times or has been in use for more than a week.<ref name=\"Rottermanner-2015-p6\">{{harvnb|Rottermanner|Kieseberg|Huber|Schmiedecker|2015|p=6}}</ref> Old encryption keys are destroyed.<ref name=\"way-transf\" /><ref name=\"te-transf\" /><ref>{{Citation|url=https://core.telegram.org/api/end-to-end/pfs|publisher=Telegram|title=Perfect Forward Secrecy|date=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nWindows and GNU/Linux users are still not able to use secret chats using the official Telegram Desktop app while the official macOS-only client supports them.<ref>{{cite web|title = Github issue 871: missing secret chats|url = https://github.com/telegramdesktop/tdesktop/issues/871|date = 2 July 2015|accessdate = 25 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nSecret chats are not available for groups or channels.\n\nTelegram's local message database is not encrypted by default.<ref name=\"Rottermanner-2015-p6\"/> Some Telegram clients allow users to encrypt the local message database by setting a passphrase.<ref name=\"zimperium\">{{cite news|last1=Franceschi-Bicchierai|first1=Lorenzo|title=Encryption Fails: When to Freak Out and When to Chill|url=http://motherboard.vice.com/read/encryption-fails-when-to-freak-out-and-when-to-chill|work=Motherboard|publisher=Vice Media|date=24 February 2015|accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Voice calls ===\nIn the end of March 2017, Telegram introduced its own [[voice call]]s. The calls are built upon the end-to-end encryption of Secret Chats. Connection is established as [[peer-to-peer]] whenever possible, otherwise the closest server to the client is used. According to Telegram, there is a [[Artificial neural network|neural network]] working to learn various technical parameters about a call to provide better quality of the service for future uses. After a brief initial trial in Western Europe, voice calls are now available for use in most countries.<ref name=\"Telegram Voice Calls\">{{Citation|url=https://telegram.org/blog/calls|publisher=Telegram|title=Voice Calls: Secure, Crystal-Clear, AI-Powered|date=30 March 2017|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Telescope (video messages) ===\nSince version 4.1, released in May 2017, Telegram offers a dedicated video hosting platform called Telescope.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/video-messages-and-telescope|title=Video Messages and Telescope|website=Telegram|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref> The round videos can be up to one minute long and autoplay. When posted in a public channel on Telegram, the videos are also uploaded to and viewable without an account. However, Telegram video messages and \"Telescope\" videos sent within non-public chats or groups are not published.\n\n=== Live locations ===\nFor either 15 minutes, one hour, or eight hours, Telegram users can share their live location in a chat since version 4.4 released in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/live-locations|title=Live Locations, Media Player and Languages|website=Telegram|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref> If multiple users share their live location within a group, they are shown on an interactive map. Sharing the 'live location' can be stopped at any time.\n\n=== Social login ===\nIn February 2018, Telegram launched their [[social login]] feature to its users, named as Telegram Login.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/login|title=Telegram Login for Websites|website=Telegram|access-date=2018-02-12}}</ref> It features a website widget that could be embedded into websites, allowing users to sign into a third party website with their Telegram account. The gateway sends users' Telegram name, username, and profile picture to the website owner, while users' phone number remains hidden. The gateway is integrated with a bot, which is linked with the developer's specific website domain.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.neowin.net/news/telegram-48-arrives-with-telegram-login-and-streaming|title=Telegram 4.8 arrives with Telegram Login and streaming|work=Neowin|access-date=2018-02-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Passport ===\nIn July 2018, Telegram introduced their [[online authorisation]] and [[identity management system]], Telegram Passport, for platforms that require real-life identification.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/passport|title=Introducing Telegram Passport|website=Telegram|access-date=2018-08-04}}</ref> It asks users to upload their own official documents such as passport, identity card, driver license, etc. When an online service requires such identification documents and verification, it forwards the information to the platform with the user's permission. Telegram stated that it does not have access to the data, while the platform will only share the information to the authorised recipient.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/07/27/telegram-passport/|title=Telegram Passport stores your real-world IDs in the cloud|work=Engadget|access-date=2018-08-04|language=en-US}}</ref> However, the service was criticised for being vulnerable to online [[Brute-force attack|brute force attacks]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/hardfork/2018/08/02/telegram-passport-passwords-crack/|title=Telegram Passport is already drawing fire for not being secure enough|last=Canellis|first=David|date=2018-08-02|work=Hard Fork {{!}} The Next Web|access-date=2018-08-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Polls ===\nPolls are a feature of Telegram that are currently available on Android, iOS and the desktop applications Polls have the option to be anonymous or visible. A user can enter multiple options into the poll. Quiz mode can also be enabled where a user can select the right answer for their poll and leave it to the group to guess. Quiz bots can also be added to track correct answers and even provide a global leaderboard<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/polls-2-0-vmq|title=Polls 2.0: Visible Votes, Multiple Answers, and Quiz Mode|date=2020-01-23|website=Telegram|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>.\n\n== Architecture ==\n\n=== Encryption scheme ===\n[[File:Explanation of secret chats (Telegram).png|thumb|200px|A simplified illustration of the MTProto encryption scheme.]]\nTelegram uses a [[symmetric encryption]] scheme called [[MTProto]]. The protocol was developed by [[Nikolai Durov]] and other developers at Telegram and is based on 256-bit symmetric [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES]] encryption, 2048-bit [[RSA (cryptosystem)|RSA]] encryption and [[Diffie\u2013Hellman key exchange]].<ref name=\"techfaq\">{{cite web|url = https://core.telegram.org/techfaq|title = FAQ for the Technically Inclined|website = Telegram|accessdate = 9 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Servers ===\nTelegram Messenger LLP has servers in a number of countries throughout the world to improve the response time of their service.<ref>{{cite web|trans-title=Telegram, the chat that competes with WhatsApp|place=[[Uruguay|UY]]|url=http://www.elpais.com.uy/vida-actual/que-telegram-chat-que-compite.html|work=El Pa\u00eds|title=Telegram, el chat que compite con Whatsapp|language=es|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> Telegram's server-side software is closed-source and proprietary. Pavel Durov has said that it would require a major architectural redesign of the server-side software to connect independent servers to the Telegram cloud.<ref>{{cite web|title = Pavel Durov, creador de Telegram: \"Ninguna aplicaci\u00f3n es 100% segura\"|url = http://www.eldiario.es/turing/moviles_y_tabletas/telegram-pavel_durov-entrevista-app-movil-seguridad_0_224677688.html|work = eldiario.es|date = 2 February 2014|accessdate = 12 February 2014|trans-title = Pavel Durov, creator of Telegram: \"No application is 100% safe\"|last = Rull|first = Antonio|language = es}}</ref>\n\n=== Client apps ===\nTelegram has various client apps, some developed by Telegram Messenger LLP and some by the community. Most of them are [[free and open-source]] and released under the [[GNU General Public License|GNU General Public Licence]] {{Nowrap|version 2}} or 3.\n\n'''Common specifications:'''\n\n* No cloud backup option for secret chat\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Platform(s) !! Official !! Source code license !! Support for secret chats !! Notes\n|-\n| Telegram || [[Android (operating system)|Android]] 2.3 or later || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv2 or later}}<ref name=Apps /><ref>{{cite web|author=DrKLO|url=https://github.com/DrKLO/Telegram|title=DrKLO/Telegram|website=GitHub|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> || {{Yes}} || Supports [[tablet computer|tablets]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsslash.com/n/2288-telegram-anleitung-so-benutzt-man-den-messenger|language=de|title=Telegram-Anleitung: So benutzt man den Messenger|publisher=Newsslash}}</ref> and [[Android Wear]] smart watches.<ref>{{cite web|language=es|trans-title=Telegram updated with Android Wear compatibility|url=http://sevilla.abc.es/mobility/noticia/android/noticias-android/telegram-se-actualiza-con-compatibilidad-para-android-wear/|title=Telegram se actualiza con compatibilidad para Android Wear|publisher=ABC|place=Sevilla|accessdate=7 December 2014}}</ref> Support synchronisation between multiple devices.\n|-\n| Telegram Messenger || [[iOS]] 9.0 or later, [[watchOS]] 5.0 or later || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv2 or later}}<ref name=Apps /><ref>{{cite web|author=peter-iakovlev|url=https://github.com/peter-iakovlev/Telegram|title=peter-iakovlev/Telegram|website=GitHub|date=18 November 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> || {{Yes}} || Launched in August 2013 for [[iPhone]] and [[iPod Touch]] and relaunched in July 2014 with support for [[iPad]] and [[Apple Watch]].<ref>{{cite web|language=es|url=https://www.cnet.com/es/noticias/telegram-se-actualiza-para-la-pantalla-del-ipad/|trans-title=Telegram updates for the iPad screen|title=Telegram se actualiza para la pantalla del iPad|publisher=Cnet}}</ref>\n|-\n|Telegram X ||[[Android (operating system)|Android]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=cpy|first1=Mujeeb|title=Telegram X for Android Released \u2013 What\u2019s New\n|url=https://ibcomputing.com/telegram-x-for-android-released/ |website=IB Computing|publisher=IB Computing|accessdate=23 January 2018|language=English|date=23 January 2018}}</ref>|| {{yes}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Telegram X: Progress through Competition|url=https://telegram.org/blog/telegram-x|website=telegram.org|publisher=Telegram LLC}}</ref> || {{Proprietary}} || {{yes}} || An alternative Telegram client written from scratch, with higher speed, slicker animations, themes and more efficient battery use.\niOS version is written with [[Swift (programming language)|Swift]]. Android version based on TDLib.\nThe iOS version was discontinued, with its code merged with the main Telegram app.\n|-\n| Telegram Messenger || [[Windows Phone]] || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv2 or later}}<ref name=Apps>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/apps|website=Telegram.org|title=Telegram Apps|accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref> || {{Yes}} || Provide synchronization between all platforms\n|-\n| Telegram || [[Firefox OS]] || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv3}}<ref name=\"gh-webogram\">{{cite web|author=Igor Zhukov|url=https://github.com/zhukov/webogram|title=zhukov/webogram|website=GitHub|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref>|| {{No}} || Based on Webogram.\n|-\n| Telegram Desktop || [[Windows]], [[macOS]], and [[GNU/Linux]] || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv3 with OpenSSL exception}}<ref>{{cite web|author=telegramdesktop|url=https://github.com/telegramdesktop/tdesktop|title=telegramdesktop/tdesktop|website=GitHub|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> || {{no}} || Qt-based desktop client. The Windows client is a traditional desktop app published in three flavors:\nWith installer, portable, [[Windows Store app]].\n|-\n| Telegram || [[macOS]] || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv2}}<ref>{{cite web|author=overtake|url=https://github.com/overtake/telegram|title=overtake/telegram|website=GitHub|date=1 December 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> || {{yes}} ||Native macOS client.\n|-\n| Telegram || [[Google Chrome]] and [[Chrome OS]] || {{yes}} || {{free|GPLv3}}<ref name=\"gh-webogram\" />|| {{No}} ||Based on Webogram, published on the [[Chrome Web Store]].\n|-\n| Telegram CLI<ref name=\"Lokot-2016-05-02\" /><ref name=\"tg-cli\" /> || [[GNU/Linux]], [[FreeBSD]] and [[macOS]] || {{No}}<ref name=Apps /> || {{free|GPLv2}}<ref name=\"tg-cli\">{{cite web|author=vysheng|url=https://github.com/vysheng/tg|title=vysheng/tg|website=GitHub|accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref> || {{Yes}} || Command-line interface for Telegram.\n|-\n|Unigram<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/store/p/unigram-preview/9n97zckpd60q|title=Unigram Preview - Microsoft Store|website=Microsoft Store|language=en-us|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/UnigramDev/Unigram|title=UnigramDev/Unigram|website=GitHub|language=en|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref> || [[Windows 10]], [[Windows 10 Mobile]] || {{No}}<ref name=Apps /> || {{Free|GPLv3}} || {{Yes}} || A [[Universal Windows Platform app]] published on the [[Microsoft Store]].\n|-\n| Telegram{{third-party inline|date=April 2016}} || [[Ubuntu Touch]] || {{no}} || {{free|GPLv2}}<ref name=\"ubuntu-telegram-app\">{{cite web|url=https://launchpad.net/telegram-app|title=Telegram app|website=Launchpad}}</ref> || {{Yes}} ||Based on TelegramQML.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://launchpad.net/telegram-app|title=Telegram App in Launchpad|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n| Sailorgram{{third-party inline|date=April 2016}}||[[Sailfish OS]]|| {{no}} || {{free|GPLv3}}<ref name=\"Sailfish Telegram App\">{{cite web|url=https://openrepos.net/content/dax/sailorgram|title=Telegram app|website=OpenRepos}}</ref> || {{Yes}} || Based on Cutegram which based on [[Qt (software)|Qt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aseman.co/en/products/cutegram/|title=Cutegram|author=Aseman Land|publisher=Aseman|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> \n|-\n| Telegram-FOSS || [[Android (operating system)|Android]] 2.3 or later || {{no}} || {{free|GPLv2 or later}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/Telegram-FOSS-Team/Telegram-FOSS|title=Unofficial, FOSS-friendly fork of the original Telegram client for Android: Telegram-FOSS-Team/Telegram-FOSS|date=6 August 2019|via=GitHub}}</ref>|| {{Yes}} || Fork of official android version replacing non-FOSS components with equivalent FOSS ones.\n|-\n| telega.el || [[Emacs|Emacs]] || {{no}} || {{free|GPLv3 or later}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/zevlg/telega.el|title=Unofficial, Telegram client for Emacs|date=6 August 2019|via=GitHub}}</ref>|| {{Yes}} || telega.el is built on top of the official library provided by Telegram: tdlib[https://core.telegram.org/tdlib]. Available as MELPA and GUIX packages.\n|}\nUsers can also access Telegram's cloud-based messages via an official [[JavaScript]] [[web browser]] interface called Telegram Web (aka Webogram). Users can share images, files and [[emoji]]s with previously-added contacts; this works in most modern browsers, such as [[Firefox]], [[Safari (web browser)|Safari]], and [[Google Chrome]].<ref name=Apps /><ref name=\"gh-webogram\" />\n\n=== APIs ===\nTelegram has public [[Application programming interface|APIs]] with which developers can access the same functionality as Telegram's official apps to build their own messaging applications.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.programmableweb.com/news/can-telegram-beat-whatsapp-public-api/2014/03/03|title=Can Telegram Beat WhatsApp with a Public API?|last=Roble|first=Patricio|date=3 March 2014|work=ProgrammableWeb}}</ref> In February 2015, creators of the unofficial Whatsapp+ client released the Telegram Plus app, later renamed to Plus Messenger, after their original project got a [[Cease and desist|cease-and-desist order]] from [[WhatsApp]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2015/02/27/whatsapp-developer-releases-telegram-forced-drop-first-project/|title=WhatsApp+ Developer Releases Telegram+ After Being Forced To Drop The First Project|last=King|first=Bertel|date=27 February 2015|work=AndroidPolice}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2015/01/21/whatsapp-now-officially-dead-receiving-cease-desist-real-whatsapp/|title=WhatsApp+ Is Now Officially Dead After Receiving A Cease And Desist From The Real WhatsApp|date=21 January 2015|website=Android Police|access-date=}}</ref> In September 2015, [[Samsung]] released a messaging application based on these APIs.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://news.samsung.com/global/socializer-messenger-app-offers-a-new-approach-to-messaging|title = Socializer Messenger App Offers a New Approach to Messaging|date = 14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nTelegram also offers an API that allows developers to create [[IM bot|bots]], which are accounts controlled by programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.programmableweb.com/news/telegram-launches-bot-api-and-platform/2015/06/29|title=Telegram Launches Bot API and Platform|last=Carter|first=Eric|date=27 June 2015|website=ProgrammableWeb}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/24/telegrams-new-platform-lets-developers-create-smart-message-bots-with-multiple-uses/|title=Telegram\u2019s New Platform Lets Developers Create Smart Message Bots With Multiple Uses|last=Butcher|first=Mike|date=24 June 2015|website=TechCrunch}}</ref> In February 2016, ''[[Forbes]]'' launched an [[Artificial intelligence|AI]]-powered news bot that pushes popular stories to subscribers and replies to search queries with relevant articles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bruceupbin/2016/02/23/introducing-the-forbes-newsbot-on-telegram/#270d46ef3117|title=Introducing The Forbes Newsbot on Telegram|last=Ubpin|first=Bruce|date=23 February 2016|website=Forbes}}</ref> [[TechCrunch]] launched a similar bot in March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/03/15/check-out-the-new-ai-powered-techcrunch-news-bot-on-telegram-messenger/|title=Check out the new AI-powered TechCrunch news bot on Telegram messenger|last=Bernard|first=Travis|date=15 March 2016|website=TechCrunch}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Security ===\n\nTelegram's security model has received notable criticism by cryptography experts. They criticized the general security model of permanently storing all contacts, messages and media together with their decryption keys on its servers by default and by not enabling [[end-to-end encryption]] for messages by default.<ref name=\"cpj-2016-05-31\"/><ref name=\"Turton-2016-06-24\">{{cite web|last1=Turton|first1=William|title=Why You Should Stop Using Telegram Right Now|url=https://gizmodo.com/why-you-should-stop-using-telegram-right-now-1782557415|website=Gizmodo|publisher=Gawker Media|accessdate=7 July 2016|date=24 June 2016}}</ref> [[Pavel Durov]] has argued that this is because it helps to avoid third-party unsecure backups, and to allow users to access messages and files from any device.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Durov|first=Pavel|url=http://telegra.ph/Why-Isnt-Telegram-End-to-End-Encrypted-by-Default-08-14|title=Why Isn't Telegram End-to-End Encrypted by Default?|date=2017-08-14|work=Telegraph|access-date=2017-10-01}}</ref> Cryptography experts have furthermore criticized Telegram's use of a custom-designed encryption protocol that has not been proven reliable and secure.<ref name=\"cpj-2016-05-31\" /><ref name=\"Jakobsen 2015\">{{harvnb|Jakobsen|Orlandi|2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Cox-2015\">{{cite web|last1=Cox|first1=Joseph|title=Why You Don't Roll Your Own Crypto|url=http://motherboard.vice.com/read/why-you-dont-roll-your-own-crypto|website=Motherboard|publisher=[[Vice Media]]|accessdate=11 December 2015|date=10 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"dailydot.com\">{{cite web|last1=Turton|first1=William|title=Cryptography expert casts doubt on encryption in ISIS' favorite messaging app|url=http://www.dailydot.com/politics/telegram-isis-encryption-cryptography/|website=The Daily Dot|accessdate=11 December 2015|date=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nCryptography experts have expressed both doubts and criticisms on Telegram's [[MTProto]] encryption scheme, saying that deploying [[Snake oil (cryptography)|home-brewed and unproven cryptography]] may render the encryption vulnerable to bugs that potentially undermine its security, due to a lack of scrutiny.<ref name=\"cpj-2016-05-31\" /><ref name=\"Jakobsen 2015\"/><ref name=\"Cox-2015\"/> It has also been suggested that Telegram did not employ developers with sufficient expertise or credibility in this field.<ref name=\"dailydot.com\"/>\n\nCritics have also disputed claims by Telegram that it is \"more secure than mass market messengers like WhatsApp and [[Line (application)|Line]]\",<ref name=\"how-secure\"/> because WhatsApp applies end-to-end encryption to all of its traffic by default and uses the [[Signal Protocol]], which has been \"reviewed and endorsed by leading security experts\", while Telegram does neither and insecurely stores all messages, media and contacts in their cloud.<ref name=\"cpj-2016-05-31\"/><ref name=\"Turton-2016-06-24\"/> Since July 2016, Line has also applied end-to-end encryption to all of its messages by default.<ref name=\"Sawers-2016-06-30\">{{cite web|last1=Sawers|first1=Paul|title=Ahead of IPO, mobile messaging giant Line introduces end-to-end encryption by default|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/06/30/ahead-of-ipo-mobile-messaging-giant-line-introduces-end-to-end-encryption-by-default/|website=VentureBeat|accessdate=10 September 2016|date=30 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February 2014, the [[Germany|German]] [[consumer organization]] [[Stiftung Warentest]] evaluated several data-protection aspects of Telegram, along with other popular instant-messaging clients. Among the aspects considered were: the security of the data transmission, the service's terms of use, the accessibility of the source code and the distribution of the app. Telegram was rated 'critical' (''{{Lang|de|kritisch}}'') overall. The organization was favorable to Telegram's secure chats and partially open source code, but criticized the mandatory transfer of contact data to Telegram's servers and the lack of an imprint or address on the service's website. It noted that while the message data is encrypted on the device, it could not analyse the transmission due to a lack of source code.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.test.de/WhatsApp-und-Alternativen-Datenschutz-im-Test-4675013-0/|title=WhatsApp und Alternativen: Datenschutz im Test|date=26 February 2014|website=[[Stiftung Warentest]]|language=de|trans-title=WhatsApp and alternatives: data protection tested|access-date=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] (EFF) listed Telegram on its \"Secure Messaging Scorecard\" in February 2015. Telegram's default chat function received a score of 4 out of 7 points on the scorecard. It received points for having communications encrypted in transit, having its code open to independent review, having the security design properly documented, and having completed a recent independent security audit. Telegram's default chat function missed points because the communications were not encrypted with keys the provider didn't have access to, users could not verify contacts' identities, and past messages were not secure if the encryption keys were stolen. Telegram's optional secret chat function, which provides end-to-end encryption, received a score of 7 out of 7 points on the scorecard.<ref name=\"EFF-scorecard-v1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/node/82654 |title=Secure Messaging Scorecard |date=17 February 2015|website=Electronic Frontier Foundation |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> The EFF said that the results \"should not be read as endorsements of individual tools or guarantees of their security\", and that they were merely indications that the projects were \"on the right track\".<ref name=\"EFF-scorecard-v1\"/>\n\nIn December 2015, two researchers from [[Aarhus University]] published a report in which they demonstrated that [[MTProto]] does not achieve [[Ciphertext indistinguishability#Indistinguishability under chosen ciphertext attack/adaptive chosen ciphertext attack (IND-CCA1, IND-CCA2)|indistinguishability under chosen-ciphertext attack]] (IND-CCA) or [[authenticated encryption]].<ref>{{harvnb|Jakobsen|Orlandi|2015|p=6}}</ref> The researchers stressed that the attack was of a theoretical nature and they \"did not see any way of turning the attack into a full plaintext-recovery attack\". Nevertheless, they said they saw \"no reason why [Telegram] should use a less secure encryption scheme when more secure (and at least as efficient) solutions exist\".<ref name=\"Jakobsen-2015-p1\">{{harvnb|Jakobsen|Orlandi|2015|p=1}}</ref> The Telegram team responded that the flaw does not affect message security<ref>{{cite web|title=FAQ for the Technically Inclined: What about IND-CCA?|url=https://core.telegram.org/techfaq#what-about-ind-cca|website=Telegram|publisher=Telegram|accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref> and that \"a future patch would address the concern\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Clary|first1=Grayson|title=The Flaw in ISIS's Favorite Messaging App|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2016/01/isiss-favorite-messaging-app-has-a-security-problem/422460/|website=The Atlantic|publisher=The Atlantic|accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref> Telegram 4.6, released in December 2017, supports [[MTProto]] 2.0, which now satisfied the conditions for IND-CCA.<ref name=\"Turton-2016-06-24\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=FAQ for the Technically Inclined|url=https://core.telegram.org/techfaq#what-about-ind-cca|website=Telegram|publisher=Telegram|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref> [[MTProto]] 2.0 is seen by qualified cryptographers as a vast improvement to Telegram's security.<ref name=\"Turton-2016-06-24\" />\n\nIn April 2016, accounts of several Russian opposition members were hijacked by intercepting the SMS messages used for login authorization.<ref name=\"Lokot-2016-05-02\"/> In response, Telegram recommended using the optional two-factor authentication feature.<ref name=\"Lokot-2016-05-02\"/> In May 2016, the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] and [[Nate Cardozo]], senior staff attorney at Electronic Frontier Foundation, recommended against using Telegram because of \"its lack of end-to-end encryption [by default] and its use of non-standard MTProto encryption protocol, which has been publicly criticized by cryptography researchers, including [[Matthew D. Green|Matthew Green]]\".<ref name=\"cpj-2016-05-31\">{{cite web|title=Why Telegram's security flaws may put Iran's journalists at risk|url=https://cpj.org/blog/2016/05/why-telegrams-security-flaws-may-put-irans-journal.php|publisher=Committee to Protect Journalists|accessdate=20 July 2016|date=31 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Pavel Durov claimed publicly that U.S. intelligence agencies tried to bribe the company's developers to weaken Telegram's encryption or install a backdoor during their visit to the U.S. in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Telegram founder: U.S. intelligence agencies tried to bribe us to weaken encryption|url=https://news.fastcompany.com/telegram-founder-us-intelligence-agencies-tried-to-bribe-us-to-weaken-encryption-4040876|accessdate=15 June 2017|work=FastCo News|date=15 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Leyden|first1=John|title=Telegram chat app founder claims Feds offered backdoor bribe|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2017/06/14/telegram_boss_backdoor_offer_claim/|website=The Register|publisher=Situation Publishing|accessdate=15 June 2017|date=14 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Telegram sent a message to all Iranian users stating Telegram Talai and Hotgram unofficial clones are not secure.<ref>{{Citation|title=\u0647\u0634\u062f\u0627\u0631 \u062a\u0644\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u062f\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0646\u0627\u0627\u0645\u0646 \u0628\u0648\u062f\u0646 \"\u0647\u0627\u062a\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645\" \u0648 \"\u0637\u0644\u0627\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645\"|url=https://www.radiofarda.com/a/iran-messaging-apps-security-concerns/29661203.html|language=fa|access-date=2019-01-18}}</ref>\n\nTelegram promised since at least March 2014 that \"all code will be released eventually\", including all the various client applications (Android, iOS, desktop, etc.) and the server-side code.<ref>{{cite web |title=Telegram F.A.Q. |url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-why-not-open-source-everything |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309205427/https://telegram.org/faq#q-why-not-open-source-everything |archivedate=2014-03-09 |website=web.archive.org |accessdate=21 January 2019 |date=9 March 2014}}</ref> As of February 2020, Telegram still hasn't published their server-side source code.<ref>{{cite web |title=Telegram F.A.Q. |url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-why-not-open-source-everything |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114013309/https://telegram.org/faq#q-why-not-open-source-everything |archivedate=2019-01-14 |website=web.archive.org |accessdate=21 January 2019 |date=14 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=r/Telegram - I think it's time for Telegram to release its server-side source code |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/Telegram/comments/a5l6hm/i_think_its_time_for_telegram_to_release_its/ |website=reddit |accessdate=21 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn June 9, 2019, [[The Intercept]] released leaked Telegram messages exchanged between current Brazilian Minister of Justice and former judge S\u00e9rgio Moro and federal prosecutors.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theintercept.com/series/secret-brazil-archive/ |title=Secret Brazil Archive \u2014 An Investigative Series by The Intercept |website=The Intercept |language=en |access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> The hypothesis is that either mobile devices were hacked by [[SIM swap scam|SIM swap]] or computers invaded.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/tecnologia/noticias/redacao/2019/06/10/como-hackers-tiveram-acesso-a-conversas-privadas-de-sergio-moro.htm |title=Como hackers tiveram acesso a conversas privadas de Sergio Moro? |website=noticias.uol.com.br |language=pt-br |access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> The Telegram team tweeted that it was either because the user had malware or they were not using [[Multi-factor authentication|2-step verification]].<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1138430205343731712 |user=telegram |title=Indeed, there's no evidence of any hack. Most likely to have been either malware or someone not using a 2-step verification password. |date=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 12, 2019, Telegram confirmed that it suffered a [[Denial-of-service attack]] which disrupted normal app functionality for approximately one hour. [[Pavel Durov]] tweeted that the [[IP address]]es used in the attack mostly came from China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-48619804|title=Telegram founder links cyber attack to China|date=2019-06-13|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019 media wrote about a numerous Telegram account takeovers of Russian businessmen that involved bypass of SMS second factor authentication. Takeover of Telegram account was also offered on dark web forums for $4000. Group-IB security company suggested [[Signalling System No. 7|SS7]] mobile signalling protocol weaknesses, illegal usage of surveillance equipment or telecom insider attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomasbrewster/2019/12/12/mystery-russian-telegram-hacks-intercept-secret-codes-to-spy-on-messages/|title=Mystery Russian Telegram Hacks Intercept Secret Codes To Spy On Messages|last=Brewster|first=Thomas|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvrain.ru/news/group_ib_rossijskie_predprinimateli_pozhalovalis_na_vzlom_perepiski_v_telegram-498660/|title=Group-IB: \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0436\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0437\u043b\u043e\u043c \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0432 Telegram|last=Inc|first=TV Rain|date=2019-12-04|website=tvrain.ru|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Cryptography contests ===\nTelegram has organized two cryptography contests to challenge its own security. Third parties were asked to break the service's cryptography and disclose the information contained within a secret chat between two computer-controlled users. A reward of respectively {{US$|200000}} and {{US$|300000}} was offered. Both of these contests expired with no winners.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://telegram.org/blog/winter-contest-ends|title = Winter Contest Ends|date = 2 March 2014|accessdate = 24 October 2015|website = Telegram}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://telegram.org/blog/cryptocontest-ends|title = Crypto Contest Ends|date = 11 February 2015|accessdate = 24 October 2015|website = Telegram}}</ref> Security researcher [[Moxie Marlinspike]] and commenters on ''[[Hacker News]]'' criticized the first contest for being rigged or framed in Telegram's favor and said that Telegram's statements on the value of these contests as proof of the cryptography's quality are misleading.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://thoughtcrime.org/blog/telegram-crypto-challenge/|archive-url = https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20140307220634/http://thoughtcrime.org/blog/telegram-crypto-challenge/|url-status=dead|archive-date = 7 March 2014|title = A Crypto Challenge for the Telegram Developers|first = Moxie|last = Marlinspike|date = 19 December 2013|work = Thought Crime|accessdate = 2 March 2014|authorlink = Moxie Marlinspike|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://tech.eu/news/telegram-protocol-cracking-contest/|title = Cracking contest: first one who breaks Telegram gets $200,000 in bitcoins (but really, nobody wins)|first = Robin|last = Wauters|date = 19 December 2013|accessdate = 2 March 2014|website = Tech.eu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.cryptofails.com/post/70546720222/telegrams-cryptanalysis-contest|title = Telegram's Cryptanalysis Contest|date = 19 December 2013|accessdate = 24 October 2015|website = Crypto Fails|last = Hornby|first = Taylor}}</ref>\n\n=== Censorship ===\n\nCountries blocking Telegram:\n{{Highlighted world map by country |CN=#8E0000 | RU=#D34343 | IR=#D34343  | IN=#D34343 }}\n{{legend|#8E0000|Completely blocked|border=1px #555 solid}}\n{{legend|#D34343|Partially blocked (some ISPs or audio traffic)|border=1px #555 solid}}\n\n\n==== Iran ==== \n{{main|Telegram in Iran}}\n\n\nTelegram was open and working in Iran without any VPN or other circumvention methods in May 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tasnimnews.com/fa/news/1394/02/21/736788/%D8%AA%D9%84%DA%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%85-%D9%81%DB%8C%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1-%D9%86%D8%B4%D8%AF%D9%87-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA |publisher=Tasnim News Agency|location=Tehran|quote=Though it is claimed by many that the Telegram is banned, but it is operating normally in Iran.|date=11 May 2015|accessdate=29 October 2015|title=\u062a\u0644\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u06cc\u0644\u062a\u0631 \u0646\u0634\u062f\u0647 \u0627\u0633\u062a|language=fa}}</ref> In August 2015, the [[Ministry of Information and Communications Technology of Iran|Iranian Ministry of ICT]] asserted that Telegram had agreed to restrict some of its bots and sticker packs in Iran at the request of the Iranian government.<ref name=\"globalvoices-08-2015\" /> According to an article published on ''[[Global Voices Online|Global Voices]]'', these features were being used by Iranians to \"share satirical comments about the Iranian government\". The article also noted that \"some users are concerned that Telegram's willingness to comply with Iranian government requests might mean future complicity with other Iranian government censorship, or even allow government access to Telegram's data on Iranian users\".<ref name=\"globalvoices-08-2015\">{{cite web|last1=Alimardani|first1=Mahsa|title=Is Telegram's Compliance with Iran Compromising the Digital Security of Its Users?|url=https://advocacy.globalvoicesonline.org/2015/08/28/is-telegrams-compliance-with-iran-compromising-the-digital-security-of-its-users/|publisher=Global Voices Online|accessdate=30 August 2015|date=28 August 2015}}</ref> Telegram has stated that all Telegram chats are private territory and that they do not process any requests related to them. Only requests regarding public content (bots and sticker packs) will be processed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-there-39s-illegal-content-on-telegram-how-do-i-take-it-down|publisher=Telegram|title=Telegram FAQ|accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref> In May 2016, the Iranian government asked all messaging apps, including Telegram, to move all Iranian users' data to Iranian servers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/05/30/iran-forces-messaging-apps-to-move-data-to-iranian-servers/|title=Iran forces messaging apps to move data to Iranian servers|last=Dillet|first=Romain|website=TechCrunch|access-date=31 May 2016}}</ref> On 20 April 2017, the Iranian government completely blocked Telegram's new voice calls, a service that allows individuals to make calls via secure, end-to-end encryption, and keep their conversations private.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iranhumanrights.org/2017/04/iranian-judiciary-blocks-popular-telegram-apps-new-voice-call-service/|title=Iranian Judiciary Blocks Popular Telegram App\u2019s New Voice Call Service \u2013 Center for Human Rights in Iran|website=www.iranhumanrights.org|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 30, 2017, during [[2017\u201318 Iranian protests|anti-government demonstrations across Iran]], Telegram has shut down a channel of the Iranian opposition that published calls to use Molotov cocktails against the police, after receiving a complaint from the Iranian government. Pavel Durov explained that the reason for the blocking was a \"no calls to violence\" policy and confirmed that criticizing local authorities, challenging the status quo and engaging in political debate were seen as \"OK\" by the platform, while \"promoting violence\" was not.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.recode.net/2017/12/30/16833542/telegram-iran-demostrations-messaging-protests-pavel-durov|title=\"Telegram is shutting down a channel that called for violent protests against Iran\u2019s government\"| date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> The opposition group promised to comply with Telegram rules and created a new channel which amassed 700,000 subscribers in less than 24 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/durov/status/947422726322565121| title=Twitter conversation between Nariman Gharib and Pavel Durov| date= December 31, 2017}}</ref> On December, 31, the Iranian government announced that Telegram has been \"temporarily restricted\" in order to \"ensure calm and security\" after the company said it refused to shut down peaceful protesting channels.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/12/31/middleeast/iran-protests-sunday/index.html|title=\"Iran restricts social media and issues stern warning to protesters\"|date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> On January, 13, the app was unblocked by an order of the president [[Hassan Rouhani]], who said that \"more than 100,000 jobs had been lost\u201d in Iran as a result of the ban on Telegram. Channels of the opposition remain operational.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iranhumanrights.org/2018/01/iran-unblocks-widely-used-messaging-app-telegram-after-two-weeks/|title=Iran Unblocks Widely Used Messaging App Telegram After Two Weeks \u2013 Center for Human Rights in Iran|website=www.iranhumanrights.org|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Iran's chairman for the Committee for Foreign policy and National Security [[Alaeddin Boroujerdi]] announced that Telegram has been targeted to be fully blocked in Iran by 20 April 2018,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://irinn.ir/fa/news/579406/%D8%A8%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%AC%D8%B1%D8%AF%DB%8C-%D8%AA%D9%84%DA%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%85-%D8%A8%D9%87-%D8%B2%D9%88%D8%AF%DB%8C-%D9%81%DB%8C%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1-%D9%85%DB%8C-%D8%B4%D9%88%D8%AF|title=\n\u0628\u0631\u0648\u062c\u0631\u062f\u06cc: \u062a\u0644\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0628\u0647 \u0632\u0648\u062f\u06cc \u0641\u06cc\u0644\u062a\u0631 \u0645\u06cc \u0634\u0648\u062f|date=2018-03-31|access-date=2018-03-31|language=en-US}}</ref> citing Telegram's role in facilitating the winter protests and the need to promote local apps.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2018/04/iran-telegram-block-filtering-protests-boroujerdi-soroush.html|title=Is Iran ready to block Telegram?|last=Staff|first=Al-Monitor|date=2018-04-02|work=Al-Monitor|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-us}}</ref> President Rouhani agreed with the need to break Telegram's monopoly in Iran, but maintained that he was opposed to a new blockade and did not see it as an effective measure to promote local apps.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2018/04/iran-telegram-block-filtering-rouhani-jahromi-opposition.html|title=Rouhani administration pushes back against Telegram blocking|last=Staff|first=Al-Monitor|date=2018-04-03|work=Al-Monitor|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-us}}</ref> Iranian MP [[Mahmoud Sadeghi]] noted that during the two weeks that Telegram was blocked in January 2018, 30 million Iranians (75% of Telegram's users in Iran) did not start using local messaging apps, but instead turned to VPN services to circumvent the block, rendering the blockade ineffective.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iranhumanrights.org/2018/04/iran-poised-to-block-popular-telegram-messaging-app-but-lacks-feasible-alternative/|title=Iran Poised to Block Popular Telegram Messaging App But Lacks Feasible Alternative \u2013 Center for Human Rights in Iran|website=www.iranhumanrights.org|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref>\n\nSince the end of the riots, the Iranian government employs a customized version of Telegram that is under their domain.<ref>{{Citation|title=\u0647\u0634\u062f\u0627\u0631 \u062a\u0644\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u062f\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0646\u0627\u0627\u0645\u0646 \u0628\u0648\u062f\u0646 \"\u0647\u0627\u062a\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645\" \u0648 \"\u0637\u0644\u0627\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645\"|url=https://www.radiofarda.com/a/iran-messaging-apps-security-concerns/29661203.html|language=fa|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 2019, Bijan Ghasemzadeh, the Iranian prosecutor who ordered the block on Telegram, was arrested for charges of corruption. It is unclear whether or not the charges were related to the ban on Telegram.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/fd6cbede80b94bbd8f7c950f6bfc2920|title=Iran arrests prosecutor behind ban on popular messaging app|date=2019-10-01|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n==== China ====\n\n\nIn July 2015, it was reported that China blocked access to Telegram Messenger. According to state-owned ''[[People's Daily]]'', Chinese human rights lawyers used Telegram to criticize the [[Chinese Government]] and the [[Communist Party of China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2015/07/13/china-blocks-telegram-messenger-blamed-for-aiding-human-rights-lawyers/|title=China blocks Telegram messenger, blamed for aiding human rights lawyers - Hong Kong Free Press HKFP|date=13 July 2015|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn August 28, 2019 the Hong Kong Internet Service Providers Association announced that the Hong Kong government had plans to block Telegram.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hkispa.org.hk/139-urgent-statement-of-hkispa-on-selective-blocking-of-internet-services.html |title=Urgent Statement of HKISPA on Selective Blocking of Internet Services |date=28 August 2019 |website=hkispa.org.hk |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Bahrain====\n\n\nIn June 2016, it was found that some ISPs in [[Bahrain]] had started to block Telegram.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bahrainwatch.org/blog/2016/06/28/leading-bahraini-isps-are-blocking-telegram-traffic/|title=Leading Bahraini ISPs are Blocking Telegram Traffic|date=2016-06-28|work=Bahrain Watch|access-date=2017-08-08|language=en-US}}</ref> In June 2017 the service faced serious pressure from Russian regulator [[Roscomnadzor]], who tried to force Telegram to register in the official telecommunication services registry, which implies serious liability for a registered party. After week-long negotiations and seeming imminent blockage of the service, the conflict ceased after high officials pulled some strings with the regulator.{{clarify|date=April 2018}} \n\n==== Indonesia ====\n\n\nOn 14 July 2017, eleven domain name servers related to Telegram were banned by the [[Indonesia]]n Communication and Information Ministry with the possibility of closing all Telegram applications in Indonesia if Telegram did not make a standard operating procedure to maintain content that was considered unlawful in the apps.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.riaupos.co/print.php?cat=11&id=156454 |title=Tak Perlu Blokir Telegram, Pengamat Sarankan Cara Ini kepada Mekominfo |author=Boy Riza Utama |date=July 15, 2017}}</ref> In August 2017, Indonesian Government has opened full access of Telegram, after Telegram has made self censorship about negative contents mainly radicalism and terrorism. Telegram said that about 10 channels/groups have been deleted from Telegram everyday due to are categorized as negative contents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tribunnews.com/nasional/2017/08/10/telegram-setiap-hari-hapus-10-grup-di-indonesia-terkait-konten-radikal-dan-terorisme |title=Telegram Setiap Hari Hapus 10 Grup Di Indonesia Terkait Konten Radikal dan Terorisme |date=August 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Pakistan ====\n\n\nIn October 2017, Telegram was inaccessible to users in Pakistan,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://propakistani.pk/2017/10/24/telegram-secure-alternative-whatsapp-pakistan/|title=Telegram, the Secure Alternative to Whatsapp, is Down in Pakistan|date=2017-10-24|access-date=2017-11-18|language=en-US}}</ref> and as of 17 November 2017, it has been completely blocked as per instructions from [[Pakistan Telecommunication Authority|PTA]], Pakistan's largest ISP, [[Ptcl|PTCL]] mentioned this in a tweet to a user.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://propakistani.pk/2017/11/17/telegram-blocked-pakistan/|title=Telegram Blocked in Pakistan!|date=2017-11-17|access-date=2017-11-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==== Russia ==== \n{{main|Blocking Telegram in Russia}}\n\n\nOn 13 April 2018, Telegram was banned in Russia by a Moscow court, due to its refusal to grant the [[Federal Security Service]] (FSB) access to encryption keys needed to view user communications as required by federal anti-terrorism law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/apr/13/moscow-court-bans-telegram-messaging-app|title=Moscow court bans Telegram messaging app|last=Roth|first=Andrew|date=2018-04-13|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=MacFarquhar|first1=Neil|title=Russian Court Bans Telegram App After 18-Minute Hearing|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/13/world/europe/russia-telegram-encryption.html?rref=collection%2Fsectioncollection%2Fbusiness|accessdate=13 April 2018|work=The New York Times|date=13 April 2018}}</ref> The ban has been enforced by blocking over 19 million [[IP address]]es associated with the service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/19/russias-game-of-telegram-whack-a-mole-grows-to-19m-blocked-ips-hitting-twitch-spotify-and-more/?guccounter=1|title=Russia\u2019s game of Telegram whack-a-mole grows to 19M blocked IPs, hitting Twitch, Spotify and more \u2013 TechCrunch|website=techcrunch.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref> They include many used by [[Amazon Web Services]] and [[Google Cloud Platform]], due to Telegram's use of the providers to route messages. However, this led to unintended collateral damage due to usage of the platforms by other services in the country, including retail, [[Mastercard]] SecureCode, and [[Mail.ru]]'s Tamtam messaging service. Users ended up needing to use VPN to access the service as a result of the [[internet censorship]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/17/17246150/telegram-russia-ban|title=Russia\u2019s Telegram ban is a big, convoluted mess|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.privateinternetaccess.com/blog/2018/04/russias-telegram-ban-is-a-fiasco-and-its-rendering-millions-of-ip-addresses-inaccessible/|title=Russia\u2019s Telegram Ban Is a Fiasco, and It\u2019s Rendering Millions of IP Addresses Inaccessible|last=Wilmoth|first=Josiah|date=2018-04-17|website=Privacy Online News|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> On 17 April 2018, Russia asked [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]], [[Google Play|Play Store]] and APKMirror to pull Telegram from stores. App Store and Play Store refused the request of Russian government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://9to5mac.com/2018/04/17/russia-apple-ban-telegram-app-store/|title=Russia asks Apple to remove Telegram from App Store after banning the encrypted messaging service|date=2018-04-17|work=9to5Mac|access-date=2018-05-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.howtochatonline.net/news/russian-government-told-apkmirror-to-remove-telegram/|title=Russian Government Told APKMirror to Remove Telegram|last=McInnes|first=Laura|date=April 17, 2018|website=www.howtochatonline.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2018, Roskomnadzor reportedly<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://rkn.gov.ru/news/rsoc/news58106.htm|title=Roskomnadzor requires Apple to stop distributing the Telegram application in Russia and sending its push notifications|date=28 March 2018|access-date=}}</ref> sent a legally binding letter to Apple asking it to remove the app from its Russian App Store and block it from sending push notifications to local users who have already downloaded the app.\n\nOn December 27, 2018 the biggest Russian web search site [[Yandex Search|Yandex.ru]] removed telegram.org from their search results.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lenta.ru/news/2018/12/26/yandex/ |title=\"\u042f\u043d\u0434\u0435\u043a\u0441\" \u0443\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043b \u0438\u0437 \u043f\u043e\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 Telegram |date=27 December 2018 |website=lenta.ru |language=ru}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, the Government of Russia [https://t.me/stopcoronavirusrussia started using] the blocked Telegram platform to spread information related to [[Coronavirus_disease_2019|COVID-19 outbreak.]]\n\n==== India ====\n\n\nIn 2019, it was reported that some ISPs in [[India]] were blocking Telegram traffic, including its official website. <ref>{{cite web |title=Reddit, Telegram among websites blocked in India: internet groups |url=https://in.reuters.com/article/us-india-internet/reddit-telegram-among-websites-blocked-in-india-internet-groups-idINKCN1RF14D |website=Reuters India |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> \n[[Internet Freedom Foundation]], an Indian digital liberties organisation filed an RTI on whether Department of Telecommunications(DoT) had banned Telegram or requested ISPs to block traffic. The response from DoT said that it had no information on why the ISPs were blocking Telegram. <ref>{{cite web |title=Not just porn, users reveal Airtel, Jio, others also banning Telegram, VPNs and proxy sites in India |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/technology/news/story/not-just-porn-users-reveal-airtel-jio-others-also-banning-telegram-vpns-and-proxy-sites-in-india-1454105-2019-02-12 |website=India Today |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> \nThere is little transparency from the DoT and the ISPs in India around content blocking on the Internet, with the DoT using opaque laws to order content removal and the ISPs randomly removing content and  blocking websites without the backing of any legal orders.<ref>{{cite web |title=How India Censors The Web |url=https://cis-india.org/internet-governance/blog/how-india-censors-the-web |website=The Centre for Internet and Society |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Use by terrorists ===\nIn September 2015, in response to a question about the use of Telegram by [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIS), Pavel Durov stated: \"I think that privacy, ultimately, and our right for privacy is more important than our fear of bad things happening, like [[terrorism]].\"<ref>{{cite web|title = Telegram Now Seeing 12BN Daily Messages, Up From 1BN In February|url = https://techcrunch.com/2015/09/21/telegram-now-seeing-12bn-daily-messages-up-from-1m-in-february/|website = TechCrunch|accessdate = 19 November 2015|first = Natasha|last = Lomas}}</ref> Durov sarcastically suggested to ban words because terrorists use them for communication.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vesti.ru/doc.html?id=2687387|title=\u0414\u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u043e \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u043d\u0430 Telegram: \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043b\u0430\u0433\u0430\u044e \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u0441 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0449\u044c\u044e \u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043e\u0431\u0449\u0430\u044e\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b|website=vesti.ru|language=ru}}</ref> ISIS recommended Telegram to its supporters and members<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/01/europe/france-church-attack-telegram/index.html|title=Killers of French priest met 4 days before attack|first1=Margot |last1=Haddad |first2=Tim |last2=Hume|publisher=cnn.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tjournal.ru/p/telegram-jihadi |title=\u041f\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0414\u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u0434\u043b\u044f CNN \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044e \u0441 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0430 \u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0437 Telegram |website =TJournal.ru |first=Gennady |last=Zavolokyn |language=ru |accessdate =20 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csoonline.com/article/3004648/security-awareness/after-paris-isis-moves-propaganda-machine-to-darknet.html|title=After Paris, ISIS moves propaganda machine to Darknet|author=Steve Ragan|date=16 November 2015|work=CSO Online}}</ref> and in October 2015 they were able to double the number of followers of their official channel to 9,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/isis-telegram-channel-doubles-followers-172356843.html|title=Isis Telegram channel doubles followers to 9,000 in less than 1 week|date=12 October 2015|work=Yahoo News}}</ref> In November 2015, Telegram announced that it had blocked 78 public channels operated by ISIS for spreading propaganda and mass communication.<ref>{{cite web|title = Encrypted messaging app Telegram shuts down Islamic State propaganda channels|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/12004892/Encrypted-messaging-app-Telegram-shuts-down-Islamic-State-propaganda-channels.html|website = Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate = 19 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = One app maker has shut down almost 80 secret channels used by ISIS to communicate|url = http://www.businessinsider.com/telegram-blocks-isis-channels-2015-11|website = Business Insider|accessdate = 19 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/telegram-knew-isis-communicate-paris-pavel-durov-a6742126.html|title=Telegram founder knew Isis used the app to communicate before Paris attacks|date=2015-11-20|work=The Independent|access-date=2017-04-24|language=en-GB}}</ref> Telegram stated that it would block public channels and bots that are related to terrorism, but it would not honor \"politically-motivated censorship\" based on \"local restrictions on freedom of speech\" and that it allowed \"peaceful expression of alternative opinions.\"<ref>{{cite web|title = Secretive messaging app used by IS takes down posts|url = https://www.cnbc.com/2015/11/19/telegram-the-messaging-app-used-by-isis-takes-down-78-posts.html|website = CNBC|accessdate = 19 November 2015}}</ref> Telegram's usage for ISIS propaganda reignited the encryption debate and encrypted messaging applications faced new scrutiny.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Encrypted Messaging Apps Face New Scrutiny Over Possible Role in Paris Attacks|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/17/world/europe/encrypted-messaging-apps-face-new-scrutiny-over-possible-role-in-paris-attacks.html|newspaper = [[The New York Times]]|date = 16 November 2015|access-date = 19 November 2015|first = David|last = Sanger|first2 = Nicole|last2 = Perlroth}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Foges|first1=Clare|title=Why is Silicon Valley helping the tech-savvy jihadists? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/12008689/Why-is-Silicon-Valley-helping-the-tech-savvy-jihadists.html|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=9 December 2015}}</ref> It also led to [[Tabloid journalism|tabloids]] labeling Telegram as a \"[[jihadism|jihadi]] messaging app\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Campbell |first=Scott |date=26 July 2016 |title=ISIS warn London 'next to be attacked' as UK churches put on terror alert after French priest murder |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/isis-warn-london-next-attacked-8500399 |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]] |quote=Images threatening attacks in London and other major world capitals have been posted on jihadi messaging app Telegram |access-date=15 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, [[France|French]] anti-terrorism investigators asserted that the two ISIS-directed terrorists who [[2016 Normandy church attack|fatally cut the throat of a priest]] in [[Saint-\u00c9tienne-du-Rouvray]] in [[Normandy]], France, and videoed the murder, had communicated via Telegram and \"used the app to coordinate their plans for the attack\". ISIS's media wing subsequently posted a video on Telegram, showing the pair pledging allegiance. A [[CNN]] news report stated that Telegram had \"become known as a preferred means of communication for the terror group ISIS and was used by the ISIS cell that plotted the [[November 2015 Paris attacks|Paris terror attacks in November]]\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn June 2017, the Russian communications regulator [[Roscomnadzor]] hinted at the possibility of [[blocking Telegram in Russia]] due to its usage by terrorists.<ref>(in Russian) {{cite web|last1=Martynov|first1=Kirill |title=\u0417\u0430\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0422\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c|url=https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2017/06/24/72903-zanyat-telegram|website=Novaya Gazeta|accessdate=26 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Director General of Application and Informatics of the Indonesian [[Ministry of Communication and Informatics (Indonesia)|Ministry of Communication and Informatics]], Semuel Abrijani Pangerapan, said eleven Telegram DNS servers were blocked because many channels in the service \"promoted radicalism, terrorism, hatred, bomb assembly, civil attack, disturbing images, and other propaganda contrary to Indonesian laws and regulations.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Widiartanto|first1=Yoga Hastyadi |title=Ini Alasan Pemerintah Blokir Telegram|trans-title=This is the Reason Why the Government Blocks Telegram|url=http://tekno.kompas.com/read/2017/07/14/20495927/ini-alasan-resmi-pemerintah-blokir-telegram|accessdate=15 July 2017|work=[[Kompas]]|date=14 July 2017|language=id}}</ref> In August 2017, Indonesia lifted the block after countermeasures against negative content were deployed in association with Telegram LLP.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indonesian government lifts ban on messaging service Telegram|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/indonesian-government-lifts-ban-on-messaging-service-telegram|website=The Straits Times|publisher=SPH Digital News|date=11 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Telegram participated in [[Europol]]'s Internet Referral Action Day.<ref name=\"europol.europa.eu\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.europol.europa.eu/newsroom/news/europol-and-telegram-take-terrorist-propaganda-online|title=Europol and Telegram take on terrorist propaganda online|website=Europol|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> As a result, Telegram expanded and strengthened its terrorist content detection and removal efforts. Over 43,000 terrorist-related bots and channels were removed from Telegram. According to U.S. officials, the crackdown on Telegram was especially effective and seems to be having lasting impact.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/europe/struggles-regain-social-media-footing-after-europe-crackdown|title=IS Struggles to Regain Social Media Footing After Europe Crackdown|website=Voice of America|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> According to Europol, Telegram has put forth considerable effort in removing abusers of its platform.<ref name=\"europol.europa.eu\"/>\n\n===White supremacists===\nAn article published by ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'' magazine on January 19, 2020, says that the [[Anti-Defamation League]] has called Telegram a white supremacist \"safe haven\" and a valuable tool for right-wing extremists. The article said Neo-nazi and fascist hate groups were using the Telegram app to organize [[2020 VCDL Lobby day|a gun rally]] in Richmond, Virginia, on January 20, 2020.<ref>[https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2020/01/telegram-nazis-richmond/?fbclid=IwAR2xH1yfeZ1LQAh2CnExQ35rHQptBf5AgCofPBpRQsydYexSwNfi6_3NMgs Ahead of Richmond Rally, Apple and Google Are Letting Nazis Use This App to Coordinate] By Ali Breland, Mother Jones, 19 Jan 2020</ref> The neo-Nazi white separatist paramilitary hate group [[The Base (hate group)|''The Base'']] switched over to Telegram after being blocked on most social media platforms, including Twitter, YouTube, and Gab, a favorite among extremists. After a number of arrests of ''The Base'' members in January 2020, a note appeared on its official Telegram account warning people to stop posting.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/22/us/white-supremacy-the-base.html</ref> In August 2019 white supremacist [[Christopher Cantwell]] posted [[Antisemitism|anti-Semitic]] comments on Telegram.<ref>https://slate.com/technology/2019/08/telegram-white-nationalists-el-paso-shooting-facebook.html</ref>\n\nThe Anti-Defamation League notes that Telegram was founded by the same two Russian brothers who founded [[VK (service)|VKontakte (VK)]], which is known for its lack of moderation when it comes to white supremism. While Telegram's terms of service prohibit the promotion of violence, they have allowed violent videos posted by mass shooters Brenton Tarrant ([[Christchurch mosque shootings|Christchurch, New Zealand]]) and Stephan Balliet ([[Halle synagogue shooting|Halle, Germany]]), although other social media platforms had removed them. The League also points to the RapeWaffen Division channel, which openly advocates rape and murder as part of a race war.<ref>{{cite web|website=ADL.org|title=Telegram: The Latest Safe Haven for White Supremacists|date=December 2, 2019|accessdate=March 11, 2020|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/telegram-the-latest-safe-haven-for-white-supremacists}}</ref>\n\n=== Illegal uses ===\nTelegram allows users to report abusive public domain posts and deletes terrorist groups' public chats and child pornography. But Telegram does not share or redress any abusing report. Telegram is still being actively used for illegal purposes. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/telegram-app-a-safe-haven-for-cyber-criminals-kerala-police-to-hc/1775014/|title=Telegram app a safe haven for cyber criminals: Kerala police to HC|work=Financial Express}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-indonesia-security-apps-idUSKBN1AH40K|title=Indonesia to lift ban on Telegram message service over security|date=2017-08-01|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-12-01|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telegram.org/faq#q-there-39s-illegal-content-on-telegram-how-do-i-take-it-down|title=Telegram F.A.Q.|website=Telegram|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://t.me/isiswatch/2|title=ISIS Watch|website=Telegram|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref>\n\n== Telegram Open Network ICO ==\nIn December 2017, cryptocurrency blog Cointelegraph reported that Telegram was planning to launch a [[blockchain]] platform and native [[cryptocurrency]]. In January 2018, [[TechCrunch]] confirmed the news, referring to multiple sources.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/01/08/telegram-open-network/|title=Telegram plans multi-billion dollar ICO for chat&nbsp;cryptocurrency|last=Butcher|first=Mike|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2018-01-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe company put together an [[Initial coin offering|Initial Coin Offering]] (ICO)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/hardfork/2018/01/09/telegram-ico-white-paper-leak|title=Here is the leaked white paper for the massive Telegram ICO|last=Mix|work=HardFork|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref> to fund development of a new blockchain platform, to be called the \"Telegram Open Network\" (TON). The offering was organised as a SAFT (Simple Agreement for Future Tokens), selling futures on tokens to be called GRAM.<ref name=\":2\" /> A 23-page white paper<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1ucUeKg_NiR8RxNAonb8Q55jZha03WC0O/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=TON.pdf|website=Google Docs}}</ref> and a detailed 132-page technical paper<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1lqVlrgiztnA5dkOHP7-ENDKT1FgZuCUV/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=TON Technology.pdf|website=Google Docs}}</ref> for the plan were released.\n\nThe offering ran in two rounds, each taking in $850 million. Russian tech news site  calculated the first round as offering 2.25 billion tokens at $0.38 each, with a minimum purchase of $20 million, and the second as offering 640 million tokens at $1.33 each, with a minimum purchase of $1 million.<ref name=\"cnews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnews.ru/news/top/2018-04-02_pri_kakih_usloviyah_telegram_vernet_investoram|title=Under what conditions will Telegram return to investors the collected $ 2.55 billion|last1=Korolev|first1=Igor|date=2 Apr 2018|website=CNews|language=Russian|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/internet/telegram-messenger-service-raises-1-7-billion-from-cryptocoin/article/518798|title=Telegram messenger service raises $1.7 billion from cryptocoin|last1=Hanly|first1=Ken|date=1 Apr 2018|website=Digital Journal|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"verge\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/1/17186004/telegram-presale-open-network-app-ico-cryptocurrency-ton|title=Telegram has raised a total of $1.7 billion from its two pre-ICO sales|last1=Liptak|first1=Andrew|date=1 Apr 2018|website=The Verge|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2018, the firm had reported raising $1.7 billion through the ongoing ICO.<ref name=\"shen1\">{{cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2018/03/30/bitcoin-price-telegram-ico-presale/|title=Even as Bitcoin Languishes, Telegram Raises $1.7 Billion Ahead of Largest ICO Ever|last1=Shen|first1=Lucinda|date=March 31, 2018|accessdate=March 31, 2018|publisher=Fortune}}</ref> Company officials have not made any public statements regarding the ICO. As of spring 2018, the only official sources of information were the two [[Form D|Forms D]] that Telegram filed with the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2018/04/131248-telegram-files-new-form-d-with-sec-indicating-1-7-billion-will-be-raised/|title=Telegram Files New Form D with SEC Indicating $1.7 Billion will be Raised {{!}} Crowdfund Insider|date=2018-04-02|work=Crowdfund Insider|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOnly the pre-ICO rounds were conducted; the public ICO was cancelled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/telegram-messaging-app-scraps-plans-for-public-coin-offering-1525281933?ns=prod/accounts-wsj|title=Telegram Messaging App Scraps Plans for Public Coin Offering|last=Vigna|first=Paul|date=2018-05-02|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-11-11|language=en-US}}</ref> The network has yet to be released.\n\nOn 11 October 2019, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission filed an emergency action and obtained a temporary restraining order against Telegram over an alleged unregistered and ongoing digital token offering in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sec.gov/news/press-release/2019-212|title=SEC Halts Alleged $1.7 Billion Unregistered Digital Token Offering {{!}} U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|date=2019-10-11|work=U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|access-date=2019-10-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Breach ==\nAn Elasticsearch database holding 42 million records 42 million user IDs and phone numbers were exposed online without a password. The accounts belong to users in Iran, which were extracted from an unofficial government sanctioned version of telegram; was found on March 30, 2020. It took 11 days for the database to be taken down, but the researchers say the data was accessed by other parties, including a hacker who reported the information to a specialized forum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comparitech.com/blog/information-security/iranian-telegram-accounts-leaked/|title=Report: 42M Iranian \"Telegram\" User IDs & Phone Numbers Leaked Online|date=2020-03-30|website=Comparitech|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://securityboulevard.com/2020/04/elasticsearch-database-with-42-million-records-of-iranian-citizen-found-exposed-online/|title=Elasticsearch Database with 42 Million Records of Iranian Citizen Found Exposed Online|last=April 7|first=Silviu STAHIE on|last2=2020|date=2020-04-07|website=Security Boulevard|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hotforsecurity.bitdefender.com/blog/elasticsearch-database-with-42-million-records-of-iranian-citizen-found-exposed-online-22852.html|title=Elasticsearch 